// ── 365 scriptures by month/day ───────────────────────────────────────────────
// Themes: Jan=New Beginnings, Feb=Identity, Mar=Renewal, Apr=Hope,
//         May=Strength, Jun=Endurance, Jul=Freedom, Aug=Body as Temple,
//         Sep=Discipline, Oct=Gratitude, Nov=Rest, Dec=Light & Reflection

const BY_MONTH = {
  1: [
    { v:"This means that anyone who belongs to Christ has become a new person. The old life is gone; a new life has begun!", r:"2 Corinthians 5:17", d:"The word Paul uses is ktisis, a new creation, like the first act of Genesis. He is not talking about someone who cleaned up their life. He is talking about someone who died. The old self built on performance, on the approval of others, on the shame of not being enough, that person is gone. Most people live as if they are merely reformed. Paul says you are replaced. The practical question is not whether this happened. It did. The question is which version of yourself you are going to act from today." },
    { v:"For I am about to do something new. See, I have already begun! Do you not see it?", r:"Isaiah 43:19", d:"God says this to people in the middle of a desert they did not choose. Not at the edge of it. Not after they survived it. In the middle. The new thing has already begun, he says, as if they should be able to see it if they look carefully enough. What the desert hides is that something is always growing underneath the surface before it breaks through. The invitation is not to wait until the desert ends. It is to look for what is growing in it right now." },
    { v:"The faithful love of the Lord never ends! His mercies never cease. Great is his faithfulness; his mercies begin afresh each morning.", r:"Lamentations 3:22–23", d:"Jeremiah wrote this sitting in the rubble of Jerusalem. The city had been destroyed, the people exiled, the temple burned. He was not writing from comfort or recovery. He was writing from the ash heap. And from there he says: the mercies of God are new this morning. Not because anything improved. Because God's character does not change with the circumstances. That is the only mercy worth having, the kind that holds when everything else has collapsed." },
    { v:"For I know the plans I have for you, says the Lord. They are plans for good and not for disaster, to give you a future and a hope.", r:"Jeremiah 29:11", d:"The people receiving this promise had just been told to build houses, plant gardens, get married, and pray for the prosperity of the city that enslaved them. Babylon. God's plan for their good was not rescue. It was faithfulness inside captivity. The future and hope he promises rarely look like the exit you are expecting. They often look like the instruction to stop waiting for the exit and start living fully where you are." },
    { v:"I focus on this one thing: forgetting the past and looking forward to what lies ahead.", r:"Philippians 3:13", d:"Paul wrote this from a prison cell about a past that included both watching Stephen be stoned and being the most zealous Pharisee of his generation. He had more to forget than most of us. What he describes is not emotional amnesia. It is the refusal to let the past determine the next step. You are not the person who quit last time. You are the person deciding right now. That is the only identity that matters in this moment." },
    { v:"And I am certain that God, who began a good work within you, will continue his work until it is finally finished.", r:"Philippians 1:6", d:"The Greek word is epiteleo, to bring to completion, to carry through to the end. Paul uses it of God the way a craftsman uses it of his own work. God does not start things and lose interest. He does not begin a good work in you and walk away when progress is slow or the material is difficult. The confidence Paul describes is not in your consistency. It is in God's commitment to finish what he started. Your job is to show up. His job is to complete the work." },
    { v:"Seek the Kingdom of God above all else, and live righteously, and he will give you everything you need.", r:"Matthew 6:33", d:"Jesus said this to people so anxious about food and clothing that he compared them to birds and flowers. His answer to that anxiety was not a better financial plan. It was a reordering of priority. When God is genuinely first, not first in theory, first in the actual decisions of your actual day, the anxiety changes shape. Not because the need goes away but because you are no longer carrying it alone. Seek the kingdom. Let the rest follow." },
    { v:"Trust in the Lord with all your heart; do not depend on your own understanding. Seek his will in all you do, and he will show you which path to take.", r:"Proverbs 3:5–6", d:"The Hebrew for lean means to rest your full weight on something. Solomon is not asking you to acknowledge God as a general principle while trusting your own judgment with the details. He is asking you to actually transfer the weight. The promise of a straight path belongs to those who seek his will in all their ways, not most of them, not the big ones, all of them. The path appears as you walk, one decision at a time, each one offered to him before you take it." },
    { v:"Commit your actions to the Lord, and your plans will succeed.", r:"Proverbs 16:3", d:"The Hebrew word galal means to roll, to heave a heavy thing onto something stronger. You are not asked to hand your plans gently to God. You are asked to roll them off your shoulders onto his, the way you would roll a boulder you cannot carry. You still make the plan. You still do the work. But the outcome and the timing are his to hold, not yours. The person who does this finds that the anxiety of striving is replaced by something steadier." },
    { v:"Be strong and courageous! Do not be afraid and do not panic. For the Lord your God will personally go ahead of you.", r:"Deuteronomy 31:6", d:"Moses said these words to Joshua on the edge of Canaan, knowing he himself would not cross over. He was not promising easy victory. He was promising divine presence inside the fight. The courage he calls for is not the kind that comes from confidence in yourself. It is the kind that becomes possible when you know who goes with you. What you are walking into is not new territory to God. He is already there, and he will not leave when it gets hard." },
    { v:"You didn't choose me. I chose you. I appointed you to go and produce lasting fruit.", r:"John 15:16", d:"The disciples did not go looking for Jesus. He found them at their fishing nets, at their tax tables, in the middle of their ordinary lives. The choosing was entirely his. He chose first. This is not a small point. It is the foundation of everything. You are not building a case for your own worth. You are responding to a selection that was already made. The fruit he calls you to produce grows from that security, not from the pressure to earn the choosing." },
    { v:"The Lord directs the steps of the godly. He delights in every detail of their lives.", r:"Psalm 37:23", d:"The Hebrew word for directs is kun, to establish, to make firm. God does not just notice your steps. He makes them firm. And the word David uses for delight is chaphets, the deep pleasure a craftsman takes in the work of his hands. God does not merely tolerate the ordinary days. He takes deep pleasure in every detail of the life of someone who walks with him. The unremarkable morning. The faithful small decision. He is paying attention to all of it." },
    { v:"Look straight ahead, and fix your eyes on what lies before you.", r:"Proverbs 4:25", d:"The instruction is physically specific. Eyes forward. Not left, not right, not behind. The Proverbs describe comparison as one of the most reliable roads away from the life you are meant to live. Someone else's progress is not your measurement. Their timeline is not your deadline. The next step in front of you is all you need to see right now. Look at it. Take it." },
    { v:"Take delight in the Lord, and he will give you your heart's desires.", r:"Psalm 37:4", d:"The verb delight here is anag, to be soft, to be pliable, to take exquisite pleasure in. It describes the way something yields completely to the thing it loves. When you delight genuinely in God, not in the idea of God, not in religious practice, but in him, your desires begin to soften and reshape themselves from the inside. The things you want start to align with the things that are good for you. You cannot produce this by willpower. But you can practice the delight." },
    { v:"But those who trust in the Lord will find new strength. They will soar high on wings like eagles.", r:"Isaiah 40:31", d:"Qawe el Adonai yachlifu koach, those who wait on the Lord will renew their strength. Yachlifu: exchange, replace, get a fresh supply. Those who wait on God do not merely maintain their strength. They exchange the spent supply for a fresh one. They soar on wings as eagles. They run and do not grow weary. They walk and do not faint. All three speeds, the extraordinary and the ordinary, sustained by the same source." },
    { v:"I can do everything through Christ, who gives me strength.", r:"Philippians 4:13", d:"Paul wrote this verse from a Roman prison, not from his greatest success. The context is a list of opposites he had learned to live inside: abundance and need, full stomach and hunger. The strength he describes is not something he had naturally. He learned it. The word ischuo, to be strong, describes strength given from outside yourself. It is not extra horsepower in your own engine. It is a different source entirely, one that does not depend on your circumstances being favorable." },
    { v:"Give all your worries and cares to God, for he cares about you.", r:"1 Peter 5:7", d:"The Greek is epiripsantes, to throw, to hurl, to cast. Peter does not say hand your worries gently to God. He uses the image of someone throwing something they cannot carry onto the back of someone strong enough to bear it. The care of God for you is the reason you can throw, not gently set down, not occasionally release, but throw, the weight onto him. He is not indifferent to what is crushing you. That is why the throwing is possible." },
    { v:"This is the day the Lord has made. We will rejoice and be glad in it.", r:"Psalm 118:24", d:"The Psalmist does not say this is a beautiful day, or a convenient day, or a day that is going well. He says it is a day the Lord made. That is the entire argument for rejoicing. Not the circumstances. Not the mood. Not the outcome. The day itself is the gift, made by God, given to you. Gratitude that depends on good circumstances is not gratitude. It is just satisfaction. This is something sturdier: rejoicing in the gift of the day regardless of what the day contains." },
    { v:"Don't be afraid, for I am with you. Don't be discouraged, for I am your God. I will strengthen you and help you.", r:"Isaiah 41:10", d:"Count the I wills. Five of them in two verses. I will strengthen you. I will help you. I will uphold you. I will hold your right hand. I am the one helping you. God does not say these things once as a general principle. He repeats them because the human soul needs to hear them more than once. When the session is hard, when the season is dry, when you have nothing left, come back to this list. Not as motivation. As fact." },
    { v:"Now all glory to God, who is able to accomplish infinitely more than we might ask or think.", r:"Ephesians 3:20", d:"The Greek is hyperekperissou, beyond all measure, superabundantly, more than we can possibly ask or imagine. Paul is not describing a God who does slightly more than you expect. He is describing a God whose capacity exceeds the ceiling of human imagination. The problem is not that God cannot do more. The problem is that our asking is too small, shaped by past failure and low expectations. Do the faithful work. And leave the ceiling open." },
    { v:"The Lord your God is living among you. He is a mighty savior. He will take great delight in you.", r:"Zephaniah 3:17", d:"The Hebrew says God rejoices over you with singing. Not tolerates. Not monitors. Sings over. The same word used for a warrior celebrating victory. And he does this now, not the version of you at your goal, not the version who has it together, but you as you actually are today. This is not permission for complacency. It is the foundation for genuine effort. The person who knows they are already celebrated trains from a completely different place than the person trying to earn it." },
    { v:"The Lord is my shepherd; I have all that I need.", r:"Psalm 23:1", d:"David was a shepherd before he was a king. He knew what the word meant. A shepherd does not merely provide. He leads the sheep somewhere they cannot find on their own, protects them from threats they cannot see, and carries them when they cannot walk. The claim is not that you will have everything you want. It is that you will have everything you need from someone who knows exactly where it is and how to get you there." },
    { v:"Taste and see that the Lord is good. Oh, the joys of those who take refuge in him!", r:"Psalm 34:8", d:"Taste and see is an invitation to personal experience, not to secondhand belief. You can believe that food is nourishing without tasting it. But you cannot know it the same way. David is asking you to stop evaluating God from a distance and actually enter the experience of trusting him. The goodness he promises is not discovered through theology alone. It is found in the actual taking of refuge, the real act of stopping your own striving and leaning your weight on him." },
    { v:"And we know that God causes everything to work together for the good of those who love God.", r:"Romans 8:28", d:"Paul does not say God causes everything to feel good, or to look good, or to be easy. He says it works together. The word is synergeo, to cooperate, to work together toward a single end. The setback, the hard season, the failure, God is working these together with everything else toward a good you cannot yet see. Nothing is wasted. Not because every hard thing is secretly pleasant, but because the craftsman uses every piece." },
    { v:"With man this is impossible, but with God all things are possible.", r:"Matthew 19:26", d:"Jesus said this in response to a question that was really about whether anyone could be saved, not about whether difficult goals were achievable. The disciples had just heard something that struck them as absolutely impossible. And Jesus did not say it was possible with enough effort or faith. He said it was possible with God. There is a category of things that lies entirely outside human ability and inside divine power. Bring your impossible thing there." },
    { v:"So humble yourselves under the mighty power of God, and at the right time he will lift you up in honor.", r:"1 Peter 5:6", d:"The word for humble here is tapeinoo, to bring low, to place under. Peter asks you to place yourself under the mighty hand of God the way a craftsman's material places itself under the craftsman's tools. Not passive. Not without effort. But under. The lifting he promises belongs to God to give, and God to time. The pressure to arrive, to achieve, to be seen on your schedule, that is what he is asking you to set down." },
    { v:"The Lord will work out his plans for my life — for your faithful love, O Lord, endures forever.", r:"Psalm 138:8", d:"The Hebrew gamar means to complete, to finish, to bring to an end. It is the same word used for God completing creation. The Psalmist's confidence is not that his own efforts will finally pay off. It is that the God who began something in him will bring it to completion. The faithful love that drives this is olam, everlasting, without end, unconditional. On the days nothing works, on the weeks everything falls apart, his purpose for you is still in motion." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and my song; he has given me victory.", r:"Exodus 15:2", d:"Moses sang this at the Red Sea, an hour after the water closed over the Egyptian army. The song came from the middle of complete and utter relief at something only God could have done. The strength he celebrates is not his own. The song is not about how hard they tried. It is about what God did when they had no options left. Strength and song together, the discipline of effort and the delight of what God does through it, these are not opposites." },
    { v:"Wait patiently for the Lord. Be brave and courageous. Yes, wait patiently for the Lord.", r:"Psalm 27:14", d:"The command appears twice in the same verse. Be courageous and wait. Most of us experience these as opposites, waiting feels passive, courage feels active. David puts them together because the waiting he describes is not passive. It is the brave refusal to sprint ahead of God, to grasp for the outcome before it is time, to abandon the process because the result has not appeared. Waiting with faith is among the most demanding things the Bible asks." },
    { v:"He gives power to the weak and strength to the powerless.", r:"Isaiah 40:29", d:"Isaiah does not say God gives power to those who have some strength left. He says he gives it to the weak, the word is yagea, exhausted, worn out from toil. The promise is most specific at the exact point of depletion. When the tank is empty, when motivation has completely gone, when you have nothing left to give, that is precisely where this promise lives. It is not given before you reach the end of yourself. It is given there." },
    { v:"Be strong, and let your heart take courage, all you who wait for the Lord!", r:"Psalm 31:24", d:"The Hebrew chazaq, be strong, is a command to the heart, not just to the body. David is not describing a feeling that arrives. He is describing a choice the heart makes repeatedly. You do not wait to feel courageous. You choose it, and it grows in the choosing. Every time you show up when you do not want to, every time you take the harder road, the heart becomes more capable of making that choice again. The training is real." },
  ],
  2: [
    { v:"Thank you for making me so wonderfully complex! Your workmanship is marvelous — how well I know it.", r:"Psalm 139:14", d:"The Hebrew pala, wonderful, set apart, distinguished from everything ordinary, is the word David uses for what God has made him to be. He does not say this after looking in a mirror and feeling good about what he sees. He says it as a theological statement about what he knows to be true about his maker. The body you are in right now was made with the same deliberate attention God gave to the rest of creation. Worship is the appropriate response. Not critique." },
    { v:"See how very much our Father loves us, for he calls us his children, and that is what we are!", r:"1 John 3:1", d:"John says look at the kind of love the Father has given us, as if you need to stop and actually look at it to take it in. The word agape carries the weight of an unconditional commitment that precedes anything you have done. You were called his child before you became anyone worth calling. That is the most foundational identity you have. Every other identity you carry, athlete, professional, daughter, whatever, sits on top of this one. Train from the one underneath." },
    { v:"For we are God's masterpiece. He has created us anew in Christ Jesus, so we can do the good things he planned for us long ago.", r:"Ephesians 2:10", d:"The Greek word poema gives us the English word poem. You are God's poem, not his rough draft, not his unfinished project, not his ongoing repair work. A poem written by a master, every word chosen. Poems take time. They have revisions. What looks incomplete in the middle is part of the writing. The process you are in, the slow formation of body and character, is not evidence that you are unfinished. It is the nature of being carefully made." },
    { v:"You are altogether beautiful, my darling, beautiful in every way.", r:"Song of Solomon 4:7", d:"The voice speaking these words knows every part of the one he is describing. There is no idealization here, this is intimate knowledge followed by complete acceptance. No qualifications, no conditions, no except for. Entirely beautiful. God's view of you is not the view from the mirror, which only measures one thing. His view comes from someone who made every part and calls all of it good. Let that reach deeper than the surface you can see." },
    { v:"For you are a holy people, who belong to the Lord your God. The Lord your God has chosen you to be his own special treasure.", r:"Deuteronomy 7:6", d:"God uses the word segullah, personal treasure, prized possession, something set apart because of its value to the owner, not its value on the open market. You are not a project God is trying to fix up to resale condition. You are his treasure. The world's economy of worth, output, appearance, performance, does not set the price here. The owner does. And the owner calls you his segullah." },
    { v:"But you are a chosen people. You are royal priests, a holy nation, God's very own possession.", r:"1 Peter 2:9", d:"The purpose of royal priesthood in the ancient world was to stand in the gap between God and those who could not reach him themselves. Peter says this is what you are, someone who carries the presence of God into spaces where others have no access to it. The health you are building is part of that capacity. You cannot sustain that presence for others if you are depleted. You are building something that is meant to overflow." },
    { v:"You have not received a spirit that makes you fearful slaves. Instead, you received God's Spirit when he adopted you as his own children.", r:"Romans 8:15", d:"The word for adoption here is huiothesia, the formal, legal placing of a son or daughter into a family. It is not a metaphor for feeling close to God. It is a statement about legal standing. You belong to his household. The Spirit you received is not a spirit of slavery, doulos, a slave with no rights, but the Spirit of adoption, with all the access and freedom that implies. Train as someone who belongs, not as someone trying to earn their place at the table." },
    { v:"God created human beings in his own image. In the image of God he created them; male and female he created them.", r:"Genesis 1:27", d:"Imago Dei, the image of God, is the first thing Scripture says about human beings. Before sin, before failure, before any achievement or any fall. You were made to reflect something of God into the world. Not to be God, but to image him, his strength, his creativity, his resilience, his care for what he has made. Every time you get back up, you are reflecting the image of a God who is faithful and does not quit. That is not a small thing." },
    { v:"My old self has been crucified with Christ. It is no longer I who live, but Christ lives in me.", r:"Galatians 2:20", d:"The Greek is synestauromai, crucified together with. Paul is not describing a near-death experience or a very serious commitment. He is describing a co-death. The old self, the one built on the law, on performance, on the exhausting effort to be enough, that person was crucified with Christ. What is alive now is Christ living in Paul's body. This is why transformation from the outside in never fully works. You can change habits without dying. Only Christ can change identity." },
    { v:"And because you belong to him, the power of the life-giving Spirit has freed you from the power of sin that leads to death.", r:"Romans 8:2", d:"The law of the Spirit of life has set you free from the law of sin and death. Paul uses the word nomos for both, law, as in a governing principle that operates consistently. Sin and death operate by law: consistently, reliably, predictably. So does the Spirit. The same power that raised a dead body from a sealed tomb is operating in yours right now. Not nearby, not available on request. In you. The question is whether you are living like it." },
    { v:"Don't copy the behavior and customs of this world, but let God transform you into a new person by changing the way you think.", r:"Romans 12:2", d:"The Greek metamorphoo, from which we get metamorphosis, describes transformation at the level of form, not just behavior. Paul says this happens by the renewing of your mind: anakainosis, a complete renovation from the inside. The world has a script about what bodies are for, what gives them value, what makes them acceptable. That script is written in you whether you know it or not. Transformation begins when God rewrites it. Ask him to start there." },
    { v:"For God has not given us a spirit of fear and timidity, but of power, love, and self-discipline.", r:"2 Timothy 1:7", d:"The three gifts Paul names, power, love, and self-discipline, come from the same source and arrive together. The self-discipline in this verse is sophronismos: soundness of mind, sober judgment, the ability to govern yourself wisely. It is not white-knuckled willpower. It flows from the same place as power and love, and it is described as a gift of the Spirit. The person who asks for it and then acts as if they received it will find it growing." },
    { v:"You made all the delicate, inner parts of my body and knit me together in my mother's womb.", r:"Psalm 139:13", d:"The Hebrew qanah means to acquire, to create, to possess, the word used when something is made with great care and then owned with great intentionality. God did not assemble you from a template. He created and possesses every inner part of you. The specific way you are made, the particular strengths, the specific limitations, the exact body you inhabit, was knit together with the same intention he gives to everything he makes. You are not an accident of biology." },
    { v:"How precious are your thoughts about me, O God. They cannot be numbered!", r:"Psalm 139:17", d:"The Hebrew word for precious is yaqar, rare, costly, of great weight. The thoughts God has toward you are not passing observations. They are weighted with value, too numerous to count. He is not merely aware of you. He is actively thinking toward you, right now, in this ordinary moment. You were thought about today before you did anything to deserve attention. That is a different kind of being known than anything a person can offer." },
    { v:"People judge by outward appearance, but the Lord looks at the heart.", r:"1 Samuel 16:7", d:"God said this when Samuel was looking at Eliab, the eldest son of Jesse, who was tall and impressive. God had already rejected him. The standard the world uses, visible, measurable, impressive, is not the one God uses. He looks at the lev, the heart, the inner life, the place where intention lives. What is the intention behind your training today? That is what he is measuring." },
    { v:"Charm is deceptive, and beauty does not last; but a woman who fears the Lord will be greatly praised.", r:"Proverbs 31:30", d:"Charm is sheqer, deception, falsehood, a thing that does not hold. Beauty is hebel, vapor, breath, something that disappears quickly. The woman who fears the Lord is praised by the same Hebrew word used in Proverbs 31:28 where her children rise up to call her blessed. This praise is not based on how she looked. It is based on who she was. The body changes. The character built over years of faithful living does not. Build both, but know which one lasts." },
    { v:"She is clothed with strength and dignity, and she laughs without fear of the future.", r:"Proverbs 31:25", d:"The Hebrew word for clothed here is labash, to put on as a garment, to be wrapped in, to be covered by. Strength and dignity are not achievements she worked toward. They are what she wears. And the laughing at the future, sachaq, to laugh, to play, is not denial. It is the response of someone so secure in her foundation that the uncertainty of tomorrow does not threaten her. Train to build that kind of security." },
    { v:"For we live by believing and not by seeing.", r:"2 Corinthians 5:7", d:"Paul says we walk by faith, not by appearance. The word eidous, appearance, sight, visible form, describes what you can currently see. Faith is the willingness to keep walking based on what is true rather than what is visible. Progress in the body is invisible for weeks before it surfaces. Character is built in the hidden places before it shows in the visible ones. The invisible work is still real work. Keep walking." },
    { v:"I knew you before I formed you in your mother's womb. Before you were born I set you apart.", r:"Jeremiah 1:5", d:"Before I formed you, the Hebrew yatsar, to form as a potter forms clay, in the womb, I knew you. Before biology. Before birth. Before you did anything. The word for knew is yada, intimate, experiential knowledge, the kind that comes from deep relationship. You were known by God before you existed. That is the most foundational fact about you, more basic than your name, your body, your history. Everything else is built on top of it." },
    { v:"The Spirit of God, who raised Jesus from the dead, lives in you.", r:"Romans 8:11", d:"The Spirit who raised Jesus from the dead, the same Spirit, Paul says, not a similar power, the identical Spirit, lives in you. Not visits you. Oikeo, to dwell, to take up residence, to make a home in. When you have nothing left, when the tank is empty, when the motivation has completely gone, you are not left with only what you can manufacture. The power of resurrection has taken up residence in your body. Ask for it. It is already there." },
    { v:"And I am convinced that nothing can ever separate us from God's love.", r:"Romans 8:38", d:"Paul could not have made the list longer if he tried. Angels, rulers, powers, things present, things to come, height, depth, every category of threat or separation he could imagine. And he says none of them can do it. Not can do it with difficulty. Cannot do it. The love of God in Christ Jesus is not a feeling that fluctuates with your performance. It is a fixed reality that does not change when you fail, when you disappear, when you are at your worst. Train inside that fixed reality." },
    { v:"Even before he made the world, God loved us and chose us in Christ to be holy and without fault in his eyes.", r:"Ephesians 1:4", d:"Before the foundation of the world, pro kataboles kosmou, before time, before matter, before there was anything to create. You were already in the mind and heart of God. Loved. Chosen. Declared holy and blameless. Not because of what you would do but because of what Christ would do on your behalf. This is not a reward. This is where you come from. Let it be the atmosphere you train in rather than a destination you are still trying to reach." },
    { v:"So now there is no condemnation for those who belong to Christ Jesus.", r:"Romans 8:1", d:"Katakrima, condemnation, a verdict of guilty, a sentence. None of it. Not reduced, not suspended, not pending review. None. The condemnation you carry into the gym, shame about the body, guilt about missed days, contempt for where you are, that is not from God. It is a verdict he has already overturned. You are not training to escape judgment. The judgment has already been rendered in your favor. Train from that." },
    { v:"Your real life is hidden with Christ in God.", r:"Colossians 3:3", d:"Your life is hidden, kekryptai, concealed, kept secret, with Christ in God. The image is of something held in the safest possible place, inside Christ, who is inside God. The truest version of who you are is not on display for others to evaluate. It is not determined by the mirror or the achievement or the number. It is held in a place nothing can reach. This is what you protect when you refuse comparison. Your real life is already secure." },
    { v:"We are citizens of heaven, where the Lord Jesus Christ lives.", r:"Philippians 3:20", d:"Politeuma, citizenship, a colony, an outpost of a foreign nation living inside another territory. Paul says your true citizenship is in heaven, which means you are living here as a citizen of somewhere else. The values of that kingdom, dignity, service, sufficiency in Christ, are your actual operating system. When the world tries to measure your worth by your output or your appearance, you are hearing the standards of a kingdom that is not yours." },
    { v:"God saved us and called us to live a holy life — not because we deserved it, but because that was his plan.", r:"2 Timothy 1:9", d:"Not according to our works, ouk kata ta erga hemon. The calling was issued before the works existed. You were called holy and set apart not because of what you would accomplish but because of God's own purpose and grace given before time began. You are walking in a purpose older than your existence. The question of whether you belong here was settled before you were born." },
    { v:"Search me, O God, and know my heart; test me and know my anxious thoughts.", r:"Psalm 139:23", d:"Chaqar, to search, to investigate thoroughly, to probe to the depths. David is asking for complete exposure. No hidden corner, no performance for God's benefit, no curated version of himself presented for divine inspection. He wants God to see everything and to show him what God finds. This is not masochism. It is the prayer of someone who trusts the Searcher more than he trusts his own self-assessment. Ask for it. Trust what he finds." },
    { v:"Point out anything in me that offends you, and lead me along the path of everlasting life.", r:"Psalm 139:24", d:"Derek olam, the way of everlasting, the ancient path, the road that has always led somewhere permanent. David asks to be led on it. Not the comfortable path. Not the easy path. The path that leads to what is actually lasting. Ask God to lead you on it in how you train, in how you rest, in how you speak to yourself about your body. The path is real. The leading is available. Stay on it one faithful day at a time." },
  ],
  3: [
    { v:"Create in me a clean heart, O God. Renew a loyal spirit within me.", r:"Psalm 51:10", d:"David wrote this after Nathan confronted him about Bathsheba and Uriah. He had committed adultery and arranged a murder. This prayer comes from the absolute bottom of a man's life. And what he asks for is not better circumstances. Not relief from consequences. A clean heart and a steadfast spirit. He understood something most people miss: the outer life changes only when the inner life is renewed. The habit you want to build will not hold if the heart underneath it has not changed." },
    { v:"Though our bodies are dying, our spirits are being renewed every day.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:16", d:"The outer man is decaying, diaphtheiro, being destroyed, wearing down. Paul does not pretend otherwise. The body ages. Strength ebbs. This is true. But simultaneously, even as, the inner man is being renewed day by day. Anakainoo: made new, freshened, restored. Both things are happening at the same time. The investment in your body is good stewardship of something temporary. The investment in your character is stewardship of something permanent. Both matter. One lasts longer." },
    { v:"The Holy Spirit produces this kind of fruit in our lives: love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, and self-control.", r:"Galatians 5:22–23", d:"The fruit of the Spirit is singular, karpos, one fruit with many facets, not separate fruits you choose between. And self-control is the last listed, perhaps because it grows from everything before it. You cannot sustain self-discipline long-term by willpower alone. But when it is rooted in love for God and in the peace and joy that come from walking with him, it becomes a different thing entirely. Not white-knuckled. Grounded. That kind grows." },
    { v:"For you know that when your faith is tested, your endurance has a chance to grow.", r:"James 1:3", d:"The testing of your faith produces hupomone, a word that combines the idea of staying under pressure with forward movement. Not passive endurance. Active staying under load while continuing to move. This is exactly what training does to the body. You apply stress, the tissue tears, and it rebuilds stronger than before. James says your faith works the same way. The test is not a detour from the development. It is the mechanism of the development." },
    { v:"So let it grow, for when your endurance is fully developed, you will be perfect and complete, needing nothing.", r:"James 1:4", d:"Teleios kai holokleros, perfect and complete, lacking in nothing. This is the image of someone who has reached full development, who has been worked through every stage of the process. James is describing a person, not a moment. The becoming is what makes the person. Every stage has a purpose: the beginner stage, the plateau, the breakthrough, the setback. You are not behind. You are in the process that leads somewhere real." },
    { v:"No discipline is enjoyable while it is happening — it's painful! But afterward there will be a peaceful harvest of right living.", r:"Hebrews 12:11", d:"The author uses the word paideian, training, discipline, the education of a child by a parent. Not punishment. Formation. And he does not soften what it feels like in the moment: painful, not joyful. But the afterward, the peaceable fruit of righteousness, is what he fixes your attention on. Not the pain of the present process but the harvest on the other side of it. The harvest cannot come without the process. Stay in it." },
    { v:"Plant the good seeds of righteousness, and you will harvest a crop of love.", r:"Hosea 10:12", d:"Break up your fallow ground, the unplowed, unworked, hardened soil of a heart that has not been tended. Sow in righteousness. Reap in mercy. The agricultural image is precise: there is no shortcut from seed to harvest. There is work between them, and there is waiting. Every rep is a seed. Every faithful choice plants something. The harvest does not come on your schedule. But the planting is in your hands today." },
    { v:"Work hard to show the results of your salvation, obeying God with deep reverence and fear.", r:"Philippians 2:12", d:"Work out, katergazomai, to accomplish, to bring to completion through sustained effort, your salvation. Not work for. Work out, the way you work out the solution to a problem that has already been given to you. God has placed in you the capacity for something. Your response is to work it out into the open, to bring it to completion through the sustained effort of daily faithful living. Grace does not eliminate effort. It is what makes genuine effort possible." },
    { v:"For God is working in you, giving you the desire and the power to do what pleases him.", r:"Philippians 2:13", d:"God is the one working in you, energon, energizing, actively at work, both to will and to work for his good pleasure. The desire to train, to be healthy, to honor your body, even the wanting can be a gift from God, not just the doing. When the desire goes flat, this verse is the one to stand on: the power to do what pleases him is still operative even when the feeling is not. Ask for it. Then act as if it was given." },
    { v:"When troubles come your way, consider it an opportunity for great joy.", r:"James 1:2", d:"Count it all joy, hegeomai, to consider, to evaluate, to deliberately assess. James is not asking you to feel joy spontaneously. He is asking you to do an intellectual act: to look at the trial and decide that it is the beginning of something valuable. The plateau is an invitation to learn. The injury is an invitation to rest and rebuild. The hard season is the proving ground for the person you are becoming. Not every hard thing is punishment. Some of it is preparation." },
    { v:"If you need wisdom, ask our generous God, and he will give it to you. He will not rebuke you for asking.", r:"James 1:5", d:"The word aplotos, generously, describes giving that is simple and without reservation, without complicated conditions or strings. God gives wisdom to those who ask without reproach, without the implication that asking was foolish or weak. You do not have to have it figured out before you come to him. Bring the question. Ask what this body needs, what this season requires, what the wise path forward is. Then pay attention to how the answer comes." },
    { v:"I have hidden your word in my heart, that I might not sin against you.", r:"Psalm 119:11", d:"Tsaphan, to hide, to store up, to treasure in a concealed place. Not to memorize, to recite, to display. To store in the heart where it shapes the instincts and governs the reflexes before the mind has time to deliberate. The word of God stored there is what you reach for under pressure. It becomes the first response, not the considered one. What you rehearse regularly becomes what you are automatically. Practice what is worth being automatic." },
    { v:"Your word is a lamp to guide my feet and a light for my path.", r:"Psalm 119:105", d:"Ner l'ragli d'varecha, your word is a lamp to my feet. A ner: a small hand lamp that illuminates the step immediately in front of you, not the horizon. Not a floodlight. Not a map of the whole journey. Just the next step. You do not need to see where this is all going. You need enough light for today. Take the step in front of you. The light for the one after it will be there when you arrive." },
    { v:"Since we are living by the Spirit, let us follow the Spirit's leading in every part of our lives.", r:"Galatians 5:25", d:"If we live by the Spirit, and Paul says we do, then let us also walk by the Spirit. Stoicheo: to walk in a line, to be in step with, to march in order behind a guide. The Spirit is not confined to Sunday morning. He is available in the decision about whether to go to bed on time, in the choice of what to eat, in the question of what your body actually needs today. Ask him to lead in the ordinary. He will." },
    { v:"Let us not neglect our meeting together, as some people do, but encourage one another.", r:"Hebrews 10:25", d:"Episynagoge, assembling together, gathering toward a common point. The writer says do not abandon the habit of gathering with other believers, especially as the day approaches. Encouragement in the context of the letter is not a pep talk. It is the act of calling each other toward what is true, of speaking the reality of God's faithfulness into someone's present discouragement. You were not designed to pursue health, faith, or growth alone. The community is part of the design." },
    { v:"Keep putting into practice all you learned and received. Then the God of peace will be with you.", r:"Philippians 4:9", d:"Practice, prasso, to do repeatedly, to carry out habitually. Paul does not say think about what you have learned. He says practice it. There is a gap between knowing and doing that feels narrow but functions as a chasm. You can know exactly what good form looks like and never practice it until it is automatic. You can know rest is necessary and never actually rest. The peace of God accompanies the practicing, not merely the knowing." },
    { v:"Let your roots grow down into him, and let your lives be built on him. Then your faith will grow strong.", r:"Colossians 2:7", d:"Errizomenos, rooted. Epoikodomoumenoi, built up. Both words describe processes that happen beneath the surface, where no one can see them. The root system of a tree develops entirely underground before the tree becomes visible. Your private faithfulness, the consistent sessions no one applauds, the genuine prayer no one witnesses, is root work. The visible growth depends entirely on what is happening underground. Go deep before you demand visible fruit." },
    { v:"This same God who takes care of me will supply all your needs from his glorious riches.", r:"Philippians 4:19", d:"Ploutos, wealth, abundance, the fullness of what God has. Paul is not describing a God who gives just enough. He is describing one who gives out of abundance, not scarcity. The health, the energy, the strength you are building is not merely for your own sustaining. It has overflow. The people in your life need you to be whole. The surplus is for them. What are you building that can be poured out?" },
    { v:"Think clearly and exercise self-control. Look forward to the gracious salvation that will come to you.", r:"1 Peter 1:13", d:"Gird up the loins of your mind, a military image of tucking the robe into the belt to be ready for action. Peter is asking you to bring focused, disciplined attention to the way you think. Not scattered, not passive, not reactive. Intentional. The self-control he connects to this is not an act of suppression. It is the natural result of a mind that is well-ordered and alert. Practice thinking well. Self-control follows." },
    { v:"Warn each other every day, while it is still today, so that none of you will be deceived by sin and hardened against God.", r:"Hebrews 3:13", d:"Today, semeron, this specific day, while it is still called today. The writer knows that hardness does not arrive all at once. It sets in gradually, through small daily neglects, through the slow accumulation of unremarkable choices that bend the heart away from God. The antidote is the same: daily, current, specific encouragement. Not eventually. Today. Tend the relationships that speak truth to you. Do not let the drift go unaddressed." },
    { v:"We are being transformed into his image with ever-increasing glory.", r:"2 Corinthians 3:18", d:"Katoptrizomenoi, beholding as in a mirror, reflecting back. And metamorphoumetha, being transformed, metamorphosing, changing at the level of form. Both verbs are present passive: happening now, being done to you, not by you. You become what you behold. If you fix your sustained attention on Christ, his patience, his faithfulness, his refusal to quit, those qualities form in you not through striving but through looking. The looking is the practice." },
    { v:"Those who live to please the Spirit will harvest everlasting life.", r:"Galatians 6:8", d:"The one who sows to the Spirit will from the Spirit reap eternal life, zoe aionios, the life of the age to come, life that is qualitatively different and permanent. Sowing and reaping is not a metaphor for magic. It is a description of how reality works in God's design. The consistent choices that honor the Spirit, showing up, choosing nourishment over punishment, building rather than eroding, produce a harvest. Not immediately. But reliably." },
    { v:"So let's not get tired of doing what is good. At just the right time we will reap a harvest of blessing if we don't give up.", r:"Galatians 6:9", d:"Me enkakomen, do not lose heart, do not grow weary to the point of giving up. The verb describes a weariness that leads to quitting, not just to tiredness. Paul knows this is a real risk and names it. The promise attached to the not-quitting is a harvest at the right time, kairo idio, the season appointed by God, not the one you have decided is reasonable. The plant looks unchanged above ground for weeks and then the fruit appears. The faithfulness is in your hands. The timing is not." },
    { v:"Just as you accepted Christ Jesus as your Lord, you must continue to follow him.", r:"Colossians 2:6", d:"As you received Christ Jesus the Lord, so walk in him. The word paralambano, received, describes taking something from another person's hands. You received Christ at a moment in time. Now walk in him: peripateo, to live, to conduct your life, to order your days. The receiving was a moment. The walking is a series of daily decisions. The excitement of the start is not the same thing as the faithfulness of the continuation. Keep walking." },
    { v:"Work willingly at whatever you do, as though you were working for the Lord rather than for people.", r:"Colossians 3:23", d:"Ek psyches, from the soul, from the whole inner person, not from external compulsion or the desire to be seen. Work that is done from the soul has a different quality than work done for performance. The session no one will praise, the discipline no one witnesses, this is where the soul is formed. The Lord sees what happens in the unremarkable moments. Working for him rather than for people is a standard that does not require an audience." },
    { v:"God blesses those who patiently endure testing and temptation.", r:"James 1:12", d:"Makarios, blessed, enviably fortunate, to be congratulated, is the word James uses for the one who endures under trial. Not the one who avoided the trial. Not the one who performed well when it was easy. The one who stayed under load and did not collapse. The crown of life goes to the one who loved God through the hard thing, not around it. If you are in the hard thing right now, you are in precisely the place where that crown is being prepared." },
    { v:"Don't just listen to God's word. You must do what it says.", r:"James 1:22", d:"Paralogizomai, to deceive through faulty reasoning, to lead astray by a false argument. James says the person who hears without doing is deceiving himself through a failure of logic. The argument goes: I know the right thing, therefore I am doing the right thing. But knowing and doing are not the same thing, and the gap between them is where self-deception lives. What do you know today that you have not yet done? The gap is the only place to start." },
    { v:"Don't reject the Lord's discipline, and don't be upset when he corrects you. For the Lord corrects those he loves.", r:"Proverbs 3:11–12", d:"The word musar, discipline, correction, instruction, carries the connotation of a parent teaching a child they love. This is not the punishment of a judge. It is the correction of a father who takes delight in you. Yachar, to reprove, is what a loving parent does when a child is heading in a wrong direction. Receive it as what it is: the attention of someone who cares too much to let you go uncorrected. The correction is evidence of the love." },
    { v:"Joyful are those who obey his laws and search for him with all their hearts.", r:"Psalm 119:2", d:"Darash, to search, to inquire, to seek diligently. The joy the Psalmist describes belongs to the one who keeps God's testimonies and seeks him with the whole heart. Not the casual observer. Not the occasional visitor. The wholehearted seeker. Joy is the companion of that kind of seeking, not the reward at the end of it, but the experience inside it. Bring that same wholehearted quality to your health. Search for what works. Pursue it with all of it." },
    { v:"Be strong and immovable. Always work enthusiastically for the Lord, for nothing you do for the Lord is ever useless.", r:"1 Corinthians 15:58", d:"Perisseuo, to abound, to overflow, to be more than sufficient. Paul says be abounding in the work of the Lord. Not doing enough. Not meeting the minimum. Abounding. And he grounds it in a fact: your work in the Lord is not kenos, empty, vain, without result. Every faithful act accumulates. The session no one saw, the consistent week no one celebrated, the habit that has not yet produced visible results, none of it is empty in God's economy. None." },
    { v:"After you have suffered a little while, he will restore, support, and strengthen you, and place you on a firm foundation.", r:"1 Peter 5:10", d:"Katartizo, to repair, to restore to proper order, to mend what was broken. Sterizo, to set firmly, to establish with unshakeable stability. Stheoo, to strengthen, to make strong. All three of these are things God does, not things you accomplish. After the suffering, which is real and which he does not minimize, God acts. The foundation being set beneath you is set by hands stronger than yours. Trust the builder with the building." },
  ],
  4: [
    { v:"He is not here! He is risen from the dead, just as he said would happen.", r:"Matthew 28:6", d:"The angel's words to the women at the tomb are the most consequential sentence ever spoken. He is not here, ouk estin hode. He has been raised, egerthe, a passive verb, raised by someone else, raised by God. The tomb was not broken open from the outside. It was vacated from the inside. Every time you come back from something that was supposed to finish you, an injury, a failure, a season of complete loss, you are living in the shape of this morning. Resurrection is the pattern. Keep getting up." },
    { v:"We are pressed on every side by troubles, but we are not crushed. We are perplexed, but not driven to despair.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:8", d:"Paul stacks four contrasts: pressed but not crushed, confused but not despairing, hunted but not abandoned, struck down but not destroyed. Each one describes a situation that seems like it should be decisive and is not. The Christian life is not a life without pressure. It is a life in which the pressure does not have the final word. The strange, inexplicable resilience that persists inside the crushing, that is the life of God at work in a person." },
    { v:"We get knocked down, but we are not destroyed.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:9", d:"Kataballomenoi, struck down, thrown to the ground, all apollumenoi, but not destroyed, not made to perish. The distinction Paul draws is not between easy and hard. It is between hard and fatal. You can be thrown down. That is real. What is not real is the claim that being thrown down is the end. The capacity to get back up is not your character trait. It is the work of the One who lives in you. You cannot be permanently put down." },
    { v:"I want to know Christ and experience the mighty power that raised him from the dead.", r:"Philippians 3:10", d:"Paul says he wants to know Christ and the power of his resurrection, dunamis, power that produces results, the same word used for the raising of the dead. He is not speaking abstractly about a theological concept. He wants to experience this power in his actual body, in his actual circumstances, in real time. When the tank is empty and the session is impossible and the motivation is completely gone, the power that raised a dead body is not unavailable to a living one." },
    { v:"Our bodies are buried in weakness, but they will be raised in strength.", r:"1 Corinthians 15:43", d:"Speiretai, it is sown, like a seed. The body is buried in weakness and dishonor. It will be raised in power and glory. The body you are in right now is seed, not failure, not the permanent form, but the seed form. The Christian view of the body is neither contempt nor worship. It is stewardship of something temporary that will be transformed into something glorious. Honor the seed. It is going somewhere only God can take it." },
    { v:"Thanks be to God! He gives us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ.", r:"1 Corinthians 15:57", d:"To de nikou, but the victory. Paul puts the contrast in the starkest terms. Death is real. The sting is real. The power of sin is real. But the victory is given, didomi, a word of gift, not of achievement. You did not win this. It was given to you through Christ. This changes the entire posture of effort. You are not fighting to win. You are living out a victory that has already been secured. Train from that position." },
    { v:"So be strong and immovable. Always work enthusiastically for the Lord.", r:"1 Corinthians 15:58", d:"Perisseuo, to abound, to overflow, to be more than sufficient. Paul says be abounding in the work of the Lord. Not doing enough. Not meeting the minimum. Abounding. And he grounds it in a fact: your work in the Lord is not kenos, empty, vain, without result. Every faithful act accumulates. The session no one saw, the consistent week no one celebrated, the habit that has not yet produced visible results, none of it is empty in God's economy. None." },
    { v:"Because of our faith, Christ has brought us into this place of undeserved privilege where we now stand.", r:"Romans 5:2", d:"Prosagoge, access, introduction into a room, the ability to stand in a presence you could not enter on your own. You have been brought into standing grace, Paul says. Not visiting grace. Standing grace, where you currently stand, where you permanently reside. On the days you miss sessions, in the weeks where everything falls apart, in the seasons where faith is barely a flicker, your access to God has not changed. You still stand in it." },
    { v:"We can rejoice when we run into problems and trials, for we know that they help us develop endurance.", r:"Romans 5:3", d:"Kauchometha, we rejoice, we boast, we glory in. Paul says we glory in tribulations. Not we tolerate them, not we survive them. We find in them something worth glorifying in, because we know what they produce. Thlipsis, pressure, tribulation, the weight of something heavy bearing down. This kind of pressure, processed through faith, produces hupomone: the capacity to stay under load and keep moving. You are in precisely the right place when it gets hard." },
    { v:"And endurance develops strength of character, and character strengthens our confident hope of salvation.", r:"Romans 5:4", d:"Dokime, proven character, character that has been tested and shown to be genuine. The Greek word describes metal that has been through fire and come out without impurity. The character being formed in you through the consistency and the hardship is load-bearing character. It holds the hope in place when circumstances would otherwise collapse it. This is why the hard thing matters: not just the body it shapes but the character it proves." },
    { v:"And this hope will not lead to disappointment. For we know how dearly God loves us.", r:"Romans 5:5", d:"He elphis ou kataischunei, this hope does not shame, does not disappoint, does not leave you holding something that turns out to be empty. The reason it holds is what Paul says next: because the love of God has been poured out in our hearts through the Holy Spirit. Not merely demonstrated to us. Poured out in us. The hope is rooted in a Person, not in outcomes. That is the only kind that does not eventually disappoint." },
    { v:"I pray that God, the source of hope, will fill you completely with joy and peace because you trust in him.", r:"Romans 15:13", d:"The God of hope, ho theos tes elpidos, the God who is the source of hope itself, fills you with all joy and peace as you trust. Not because your circumstances are hopeful. Not because things are going well. As you trust. The joy and peace are the result of the trusting, not the condition for it. You trust first. The joy and peace come as a consequence of the trusting, not as its prerequisite." },
    { v:"Let all that I am wait quietly before God, for my hope is in him.", r:"Psalm 62:5", d:"Ach lElohim domi nafshi, only to God be silent, my soul. The word domi means stillness, a ceasing from noise and striving. David is commanding his own soul to stop its restless movement and be still before God. This is not passivity. It is the active choice to stop striving, to stop grasping, to stop managing the outcome yourself. The waiting that David describes renews hope not because something changes but because you stop trying to be the thing that changes it." },
    { v:"He alone is my rock and my salvation, my fortress where I will not be shaken.", r:"Psalm 62:6", d:"Rock, tsur, a massive outcropping of stone, immovable, impossible to shift. Salvation, yeshua, deliverance, safety. Fortress, misgab, a high place of refuge beyond the reach of enemies. David is stacking images of absolute stability. And he says: I shall not be greatly shaken. Not I will never be shaken. But I will not be greatly moved. There is a foundation beneath you that does not move when everything else does. Build your identity on that, not on your performance." },
    { v:"Why am I discouraged? Why is my heart so sad? I will put my hope in God!", r:"Psalm 42:11", d:"David talks to his own soul, lamah tishtoahahi nafshi, why are you cast down, O my soul? He names the depression honestly and then redirects it deliberately. Why are you in turmoil within me? Hope in God, yakhal, to wait with expectation, to hold yourself toward something coming. This is one of the most practical acts in the Psalms: catching the spiral, naming it, and choosing to reorient toward truth. You are allowed to name the discouragement. Then talk back to it with something real." },
    { v:"O Lord, you alone are my hope. I've trusted you, O Lord, from childhood.", r:"Psalm 71:5", d:"Ki attah tiqvati, for you are my hope. Tiqvah: hope, expectation, something stretched forward toward what is coming, like a cord pulled taut. David's hope is not in the outcome of his circumstances. It is in God himself, in who God is, not in what God will do in the way David prefers. That is the only hope that holds regardless of outcome. Place yours there." },
    { v:"I will keep on hoping for your help; I will praise you more and more.", r:"Psalm 71:14", d:"Keep on, a commitment renewed rather than a feeling sustained. Hope is the choice you make again in every ordinary day when circumstances are not cooperating. Praise that increases is the response of someone who has found that hope held. Let your praise grow in proportion to what God has sustained you through." },
    { v:"The Lord is good to those who depend on him, to those who search for him.", r:"Lamentations 3:25", d:"Tov Adonai l'qovav, the Lord is good to those who wait for him. Qavah: to wait, to hope, to be bound together with, like strands twisted into rope. The goodness of God is not uniformly distributed. It is specifically accessible to those who actually wait, who actually seek, who depend in the most literal sense. Not those who acknowledge that depending is a good idea. Those who do it. Depend. Seek. Receive what is available there." },
    { v:"So it is good to wait quietly for salvation from the Lord.", r:"Lamentations 3:26", d:"Tov v'yachel v'dumam, it is good, and he waits, and is silent. The waiting that is good is not resignation. It is the active, quiet trust of someone who believes the outcome is in better hands than their own. The recovery day, the week with no visible progress, the plateau that continues past what seems reasonable, these are not failures of effort. They are practiced trust. God calls them good." },
    { v:"Our present troubles are small and won't last very long. Yet they produce for us a glory that vastly outweighs them.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:17", d:"Parachreema kai elaphron, momentary and light. Paul says this about suffering that included beatings, shipwrecks, and imprisonment. His perspective was not detachment or denial. It was a longer view: the weight of glory, baros doxes, a phrase that borrows from the Hebrew kabod, the heavy, weighty presence of God, is incommensurably greater than the present suffering. The present trouble is producing something. It is doing more than it looks like from where you are standing." },
    { v:"We fix our gaze on things that cannot be seen. For the things we see now will soon be gone, but the things we cannot see will last forever.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:18", d:"Me ta blepomena alla ta me blepomena, not the things seen but the things not seen. Paul asks you to make a deliberate choice about where you fix your sustained attention. The seen things are real but temporary. The unseen things are real and eternal. Fix your gaze, skopeo, to aim at, to mark, on the character being formed, on the faithfulness being established, on the God who sees what is not yet visible. The practice of hope is the practice of looking in the right direction." },
    { v:"Always be full of joy in the Lord. I say it again — rejoice!", r:"Philippians 4:4", d:"Chairete, rejoice. He says it twice. En kyrio, in the Lord. The location of the rejoicing is inside your relationship with him, not inside your circumstances. That is what makes it a command rather than a mood: it is not contingent on how today is going. The Lord is the ground of it, not the outcome. You can rejoice on a bad training day. You can rejoice in a season of slow progress. Because the Lord in whom you rejoice has not changed." },
    { v:"I have told you all this so that you may have peace in me. Take heart, because I have overcome the world.", r:"John 16:33", d:"En to kosmo thlipsin exete, in the world you will have tribulation. Jesus does not promise otherwise. What he says is: I have overcome the world, nenikekai, perfect tense, already done, a completed act. The overcoming has already happened. The tribulation you face is real, but it is fighting against a victory that has already been won. You are not trying to win. You are living in the wake of a victory already secured. Take heart from that." },
    { v:"No, despite all these things, overwhelming victory is ours through Christ, who loved us.", r:"Romans 8:37", d:"Hypernikomen, we more than conquer, we overwhelm in the conquest, we are super-victors. Paul uses the word dia, through, Christ who loved us. Not by our own effort. Not by our performance. Through him. The love of Christ is the means of the victory, not just the motivation for it. The hard season, the disappointing result, the struggle that will not resolve, these are not evidence against the victory. They are terrain inside of it." },
    { v:"For every child of God defeats this evil world, and we achieve this victory through our faith.", r:"1 John 5:4", d:"Nike, victory. The word from which a shoe company got its name. The victory that overcomes the world is our faith, he pistis hemon, the specific faith we have. Not faith as a general feeling of optimism. Faith in the specific truth of who God is and what he has done. That faith is not compatible with the world's system of worth, comparison, and earning. Every time you train from identity instead of insecurity, you are overcoming." },
    { v:"The Spirit who lives in you is greater than the spirit who lives in the world.", r:"1 John 4:4", d:"Meizon, greater, larger, more powerful. The Spirit who lives in you, ho on en humin, is greater than the spirit operating in the world. This is not a close contest. The one in you is greater than the one in the world. The voices of shame, the comparison trap, the lie that you are not enough, these are the spirit of the world. The Spirit of God in you exceeds all of it. Live from that position." },
    { v:"For our present troubles are producing for us a glory that vastly outweighs them and will last forever!", r:"2 Corinthians 4:17", d:"Parachreema kai elaphron, momentary and light. Paul says this about suffering that included beatings, shipwrecks, and imprisonment. His perspective was not detachment or denial. It was a longer view: the weight of glory, baros doxes, a phrase that borrows from the Hebrew kabod, the heavy, weighty presence of God, is incommensurably greater than the present suffering. The present trouble is producing something. It is doing more than it looks like from where you are standing." },
    { v:"Being confident of this, that he who began a good work in you will carry it on to completion.", r:"Philippians 1:6", d:"The Greek word is epiteleo, to bring to completion, to carry through to the end. Paul uses it of God the way a craftsman uses it of his own work. God does not start things and lose interest. He does not begin a good work in you and walk away when progress is slow or the material is difficult. The confidence Paul describes is not in your consistency. It is in God's commitment to finish what he started. Your job is to show up. His job is to complete the work." },
    { v:"The Lord is my light and my salvation — so why should I be afraid?", r:"Psalm 27:1", d:"Ori v'yishi, my light and my salvation. Ori, my light, the one who illuminates the path. Yishi, my salvation, the one who delivers me from what threatens. Both from the same person. The question David asks at the end, m'mi ira, of whom shall I be afraid, is not rhetorical. It expects an answer. The answer is: no one. When your light and your salvation are the same person, and that person is God, fear has no ground to stand on." },
    { v:"Everything written in the Scriptures was written to teach us, so that we might have hope.", r:"Romans 15:4", d:"Eis ten hemetera didaskalian, for our teaching. Everything written in the Scriptures before your time was written with you in mind. The stories of those who endured, who came back after falling, who found God faithful in the desert and in the exile and in the prison, they were preserved and given to you so that you would have hope. You are not the first person to find this hard. Learn from the endurance of everyone who came before you." },
  ],
  5: [
    { v:"This is my command — be strong and courageous! Do not be afraid or discouraged. For the Lord your God is with you wherever you go.", r:"Joshua 1:9", d:"Chazaq v'amats, be strong and courageous. The command appears four times in the first chapter of Joshua. Not because Joshua was a coward. Because the task was genuinely terrifying and the temptation to shrink from it was real. The reason given is not your capability. It is ki Adonai Eloheicha imach, because the Lord your God is with you wherever you go. The courage becomes possible not because you are sufficient but because you are accompanied by someone who is." },
    { v:"Be on guard. Stand firm in the faith. Be courageous. Be strong.", r:"1 Corinthians 16:13", d:"Gregoreite, be watchful, stay awake. Stekete, stand firm, hold your ground. Andrizesthe, be courageous, act like men of valor. Krataiousthe, be made strong, be strengthened. Four imperatives in sequence. Not suggestions, not aspirations. Commands to be obeyed in the present moment. Paul wrote these to ordinary people in a city famous for its moral complexity. The commands do not wait for the circumstances to be favorable." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and my song; he has given me victory.", r:"Exodus 15:2", d:"Moses sang this at the Red Sea, an hour after the water closed over the Egyptian army. The song came from the middle of complete and utter relief at something only God could have done. The strength he celebrates is not his own. The song is not about how hard they tried. It is about what God did when they had no options left. Strength and song together, the discipline of effort and the delight of what God does through it, these are not opposites." },
    { v:"Be strong in the Lord and in his mighty power.", r:"Ephesians 6:10", d:"Endunamouesthe, be strengthened, be empowered, receive strength. The passive voice matters: this is not strength you produce. It is strength you receive. En kurio, in the Lord. The strength Paul is describing is not located in you. It is located in Christ, and you access it by being in him. When you reach the edge of your own capacity, you have not reached the edge of what is available. You have reached the boundary of the wrong source." },
    { v:"God is our refuge and strength, always ready to help in times of trouble.", r:"Psalm 46:1", d:"Matzah meod, found to be very much, abundantly available. God is not just a help in trouble. He is an ever-present help, always to be found, immediately accessible when trouble comes. The hard session is not evidence of his absence. It may be exactly the place where his presence is most tangible because that is where you most acutely need it. Enter the hard thing knowing you are not going in alone." },
    { v:"The Lord gives his people strength. The Lord blesses them with peace.", r:"Psalm 29:11", d:"Oz, strength, the kind that prevails. Shalom, peace, wholeness, the complete flourishing of the person. Both from the same source, given together. The God who equips you for the effort also provides the rest that restores. These are not competing gifts, as if you must choose between strength for the work and peace for the recovery. They come from the same hand. Receive both." },
    { v:"My health may fail, and my spirit may grow weak, but God remains the strength of my heart.", r:"Psalm 73:26", d:"She'er levavi, my heart and my flesh may fail. Asaph does not pretend the body is invincible. He writes with the clear-eyed knowledge that the outer person has limits. But God is tzur levavi, the rock of my heart, the strength of my heart, and my portion forever. There is an interior strength available that outlasts the body. Build both. Know which one lasts." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and my shield. I trust him with all my heart.", r:"Psalm 28:7", d:"Adonai uzi umaginni, the Lord is my strength and my shield. Uzi: my strength, my force, my power. Maginni: my shield, my protection. Offense and defense from the same source. The God who equips you for the effort is also the protection in your vulnerability. When you are weak, you are not exposed. The shield is still there. Trust him with the full range: the strong days and the weak ones." },
    { v:"He gives power to the weak and strength to the powerless.", r:"Isaiah 40:29", d:"Isaiah does not say God gives power to those who have some strength left. He says he gives it to the weak, the word is yagea, exhausted, worn out from toil. The promise is most specific at the exact point of depletion. When the tank is empty, when motivation has completely gone, when you have nothing left to give, that is precisely where this promise lives. It is not given before you reach the end of yourself. It is given there." },
    { v:"Don't be afraid, for I am with you. Don't be discouraged, for I am your God. I will strengthen you and help you.", r:"Isaiah 41:10", d:"Count the I wills. Five of them in two verses. I will strengthen you. I will help you. I will uphold you. I will hold your right hand. I am the one helping you. God does not say these things once as a general principle. He repeats them because the human soul needs to hear them more than once. When the session is hard, when the season is dry, when you have nothing left, come back to this list. Not as motivation. As fact." },
    { v:"For I hold you by your right hand — I, the Lord your God. And I say to you, Don't be afraid. I am here to help you.", r:"Isaiah 41:13", d:"Ki ani Adonai Eloheicha machaziq yeminecha, for I, the Lord your God, hold your right hand. The right hand in the ancient world was the hand of power and action. God is holding that hand. Not standing nearby and offering encouragement. Holding it. And saying: do not fear. Ani azartika, I am the one helping you. Present tense, right now, in this moment. You are not holding yourself up." },
    { v:"The Sovereign Lord is my strength! He makes me as surefooted as a deer, able to tread upon the heights.", r:"Habakkuk 3:19", d:"Adonai Elohim cheli, the Lord God is my strength. And he makes my feet like the deer's, suros, sure-footed on difficult and high terrain. The deer does not climb the high places by being careful. It is made for them. God makes you capable of the terrain you are on. The height of what is in front of you is not evidence that you are in the wrong place. It is evidence that you were made for it." },
    { v:"Through God we will do valiantly, and it is he who shall tread down our foes.", r:"Psalm 60:12", d:"Through God we will do valiantly, not cautiously, not half-heartedly, but with courage that does not hold back. The valor here is not recklessness. It is wholehearted effort in partnership with One who goes before you. Bring everything you have today. Do it in his strength." },
    { v:"I can do everything through Christ, who gives me strength.", r:"Philippians 4:13", d:"Paul wrote this verse from a Roman prison, not from his greatest success. The context is a list of opposites he had learned to live inside: abundance and need, full stomach and hunger. The strength he describes is not something he had naturally. He learned it. The word ischuo, to be strong, describes strength given from outside yourself. It is not extra horsepower in your own engine. It is a different source entirely, one that does not depend on your circumstances being favorable." },
    { v:"My grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness.", r:"2 Corinthians 12:9", d:"Dunamis en astheneia teleitai, power is perfected in weakness. The word teleitai means brought to completion, fulfilled, achieved its end. Weakness is not the obstacle to God's power. It is the precise location where his power achieves its fullest expression. The limitation you are trying to hide is the exact place where he shows up most clearly. Stop hiding it. Offer it. That is where he works." },
    { v:"Therefore I will boast all the more gladly about my weaknesses, so that Christ's power may rest on me.", r:"2 Corinthians 12:9", d:"Dunamis en astheneia teleitai, power is perfected in weakness. The word teleitai means brought to completion, fulfilled, achieved its end. Weakness is not the obstacle to God's power. It is the precise location where his power achieves its fullest expression. The limitation you are trying to hide is the exact place where he shows up most clearly. Stop hiding it. Offer it. That is where he works." },
    { v:"With your help I can advance against a troop; with my God I can scale a wall.", r:"Psalm 18:29", d:"Ki vecha arutz gedud, through you I can charge a troop. Uveilohay adaleq shur, through my God I can leap over a wall. The wall in front of you, the goal that seems too high, the standard you cannot quite reach, is scalable. Not by you alone. But with the God who has already been to the other side of every wall you will ever face. The obstacle is real. So is the provision." },
    { v:"The Lord will fight for you; you need only to be still.", r:"Exodus 14:14", d:"Adonai yilachem lachem, the Lord will fight for you. V'atem tacharishun, and you will be still. Moses said this to people standing between the Egyptian army and the Red Sea. Their options were exactly zero. And the command was: be still. The hardest thing is sometimes to stop striving in your own strength and let God do what you cannot. Know the difference between what is yours to do and what is his. Do yours. Let him do his." },
    { v:"No, despite all these things, overwhelming victory is ours through Christ, who loved us.", r:"Romans 8:37", d:"Hypernikomen, we more than conquer, we overwhelm in the conquest, we are super-victors. Paul uses the word dia, through, Christ who loved us. Not by our own effort. Not by our performance. Through him. The love of Christ is the means of the victory, not just the motivation for it. The hard season, the disappointing result, the struggle that will not resolve, these are not evidence against the victory. They are terrain inside of it." },
    { v:"For every child of God defeats this evil world, and we achieve this victory through our faith.", r:"1 John 5:4", d:"Nike, victory. The word from which a shoe company got its name. The victory that overcomes the world is our faith, he pistis hemon, the specific faith we have. Not faith as a general feeling of optimism. Faith in the specific truth of who God is and what he has done. That faith is not compatible with the world's system of worth, comparison, and earning. Every time you train from identity instead of insecurity, you are overcoming." },
    { v:"You belong to God. You have already won a victory, because the Spirit who lives in you is greater than the spirit who lives in the world.", r:"1 John 4:4", d:"Meizon, greater, larger, more powerful. The Spirit who lives in you, ho on en humin, is greater than the spirit operating in the world. This is not a close contest. The one in you is greater than the one in the world. The voices of shame, the comparison trap, the lie that you are not enough, these are the spirit of the world. The Spirit of God in you exceeds all of it. Live from that position." },
    { v:"I go before you and will level the mountains; I will break down gates of bronze and cut through bars of iron.", r:"Isaiah 45:2", d:"He goes before you. The new season, the new goal, the unfamiliar challenge, God has already been there. You are not stepping into uncharted territory. You are following someone who has already walked it. The path ahead has already been trodden by someone who will not abandon you. Follow without fear." },
    { v:"Be strong and courageous, for you are the one who will lead these people.", r:"Joshua 1:6", d:"Chazaq ki attah tanchil et ha'am hazeh, be strong, for you will lead this people. The courage Joshua is called to is not for his own benefit. It is because the people behind him are counting on him to lead. Your health, your strength, your faithfulness have downstream effects. The children, the clients, the friends, the family, they need you to show up at your full capacity. The courage is not only personal. It is for them." },
    { v:"I have fought the good fight, I have finished the race, and I have remained faithful.", r:"2 Timothy 4:7", d:"Ton agona ton kalon egonismai, I have fought the good fight. Ton dromon teteleka, I have finished the course. Ten pistin teterekai, I have kept the faith. Three perfects, past actions with present effects. He fought, and the fight stands completed. He ran, and the race stands finished. He kept the faith, and the faith stands kept. Not the most impressive metrics. Not the most brilliant career. These three things. They are worth building toward." },
    { v:"And now the prize awaits me — the crown of righteousness, which the Lord, the righteous Judge, will give me.", r:"2 Timothy 4:8", d:"Apokeitai moi, laid up for me, stored away, waiting. The crown is already in place. It is being kept for the one who finishes. Paul's confidence is in the righteousness of the Judge, not in his own perfection. The crown is given to those who have loved his appearing, who lived in hopeful anticipation of what is coming. Let that expectation shape how you run today." },
    { v:"I discipline my body like an athlete, training it to do what it should.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:27", d:"Hupopiazo mou to soma, I discipline my body, I treat it roughly, I bring it under control. And doulagogo, I make it my slave, I bring it into submission. Paul takes the possibility of disqualification seriously enough to train his body with intentionality. The message he carried and the life he lived had to be coherent. The same is true for you. Your private discipline either aligns with or contradicts who you say you are." },
    { v:"So I run with purpose in every step. I am not just shadowboxing.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:26", d:"Outo trecho hos ouk adelos, I run, but not as uncertainly, not without a clear aim. Houtoos pukteuo hos ouk aera deron, I box, but not as striking air. Purpose in every step. Paul is not going through motions. He is not filling hours. Every session has an intention, every movement has a reason. This is what separates training that transforms from activity that merely passes time. Know why you are doing what you are doing." },
    { v:"Wait patiently for the Lord. Be brave and courageous. Yes, wait patiently for the Lord.", r:"Psalm 27:14", d:"The command appears twice in the same verse. Be courageous and wait. Most of us experience these as opposites, waiting feels passive, courage feels active. David puts them together because the waiting he describes is not passive. It is the brave refusal to sprint ahead of God, to grasp for the outcome before it is time, to abandon the process because the result has not appeared. Waiting with faith is among the most demanding things the Bible asks." },
    { v:"What shall we say? If God is for us, who can ever be against us?", r:"Romans 8:31", d:"Ei ho theos hyper hemon, tis kath hemon, if God is for us, who can be against us? Paul does not say no one will oppose you. He says no one can prevail against you. There is a difference. The scale, the comparison, the voice that says you are not enough, these are real. But the God who is actively, personally for you, hyper hemon, exceeds all opposition. Stand on the reality of who is for you." },
    { v:"The Lord your God is in your midst, a mighty one who will save.", r:"Zephaniah 3:17", d:"The Hebrew says God rejoices over you with singing. Not tolerates. Not monitors. Sings over. The same word used for a warrior celebrating victory. And he does this now, not the version of you at your goal, not the version who has it together, but you as you actually are today. This is not permission for complacency. It is the foundation for genuine effort. The person who knows they are already celebrated trains from a completely different place than the person trying to earn it." },
    { v:"Be strong and courageous! Do not be frightened, and do not be dismayed, for the Lord your God is with you wherever you go.", r:"Joshua 1:9", d:"Chazaq v'amats, be strong and courageous. The command appears four times in the first chapter of Joshua. Not because Joshua was a coward. Because the task was genuinely terrifying and the temptation to shrink from it was real. The reason given is not your capability. It is ki Adonai Eloheicha imach, because the Lord your God is with you wherever you go. The courage becomes possible not because you are sufficient but because you are accompanied by someone who is." },
  ],
  6: [
    { v:"Let us run with endurance the race God has set before us.", r:"Hebrews 12:1", d:"Trecho ton prokeimenon hemin agona, let us run the race set before us. Ton prokeimenon, the one set before us specifically, the one appointed for us. Not someone else's race. Yours. The cloud of witnesses watching is not a pressure to perform. It is the testimony that this race can be run, that people before you have finished it, that the finish line is real. Run your own race. Comparison will make you lose it." },
    { v:"We do this by keeping our eyes on Jesus, the champion who initiates and perfects our faith.", r:"Hebrews 12:2", d:"Aphorontes eis ton tes pisteos archegon kai teleioten Iesoun, looking away from everything else and toward Jesus, the author and perfecter of our faith. Aphorontes: looking away from everything else in order to fix your gaze on one thing. He authored the faith, began it in you. He will perfect it, bring it to completion. In the long middle of the race where nothing dramatic is happening, fix your gaze on the one who started this and will finish it." },
    { v:"Think of all the hostility he endured from sinful people; then you won't become weary and give up.", r:"Hebrews 12:3", d:"Analogisasthe, consider carefully, reason through, think with sustained attention. Think about the one who endured such hostility from sinners against himself. Not to produce guilt. But to produce perspective. Whatever you are enduring today sits on a much smaller scale than what he endured. And he did not quit. That is the permission you need to take the next step." },
    { v:"Don't you realize that in a race everyone runs, but only one person gets the prize? So run to win!", r:"1 Corinthians 9:24", d:"Houtoos trechete hina katalabete, run in such a way that you may win. Not run in such a way that you show up. Not run in a way that demonstrates effort. In such a way that you win. Paul applies the discipline of the serious athlete to the whole of the Christian life. The serious athlete does not hold back on the training. They go after the prize. Go after the life you are called to with the same wholehearted intent." },
    { v:"All athletes are disciplined in their training. They do it to win a prize that will fade away, but we do it for an eternal prize.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:25", d:"Pas ho agonizomenos panta egkrateuetai, every athlete exercises self-control in all things. All things, not the things he feels like controlling. All. The one who trains for a prize that will rust shows more discipline than most people ever summon. And you are training for something that does not rust. Let the eternal prize motivate a deeper and more sustained discipline than any temporary reward could produce." },
    { v:"So I run with purpose in every step. I am not just shadowboxing.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:26", d:"Outo trecho hos ouk adelos, I run, but not as uncertainly, not without a clear aim. Houtoos pukteuo hos ouk aera deron, I box, but not as striking air. Purpose in every step. Paul is not going through motions. He is not filling hours. Every session has an intention, every movement has a reason. This is what separates training that transforms from activity that merely passes time. Know why you are doing what you are doing." },
    { v:"I discipline my body like an athlete, training it to do what it should.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:27", d:"Hupopiazo mou to soma, I discipline my body, I treat it roughly, I bring it under control. And doulagogo, I make it my slave, I bring it into submission. Paul takes the possibility of disqualification seriously enough to train his body with intentionality. The message he carried and the life he lived had to be coherent. The same is true for you. Your private discipline either aligns with or contradicts who you say you are." },
    { v:"We can rejoice, too, when we run into problems and trials, for we know that they help us develop endurance.", r:"Romans 5:3", d:"Kauchometha, we rejoice, we boast, we glory in. Paul says we glory in tribulations. Not we tolerate them, not we survive them. We find in them something worth glorifying in, because we know what they produce. Thlipsis, pressure, tribulation, the weight of something heavy bearing down. This kind of pressure, processed through faith, produces hupomone: the capacity to stay under load and keep moving. You are in precisely the right place when it gets hard." },
    { v:"Patient endurance is what you need now, so that you will continue to do God's will.", r:"Hebrews 10:36", d:"Hupomone gar humin chreian echete, for you have need of endurance. Not inspiration. Not intensity. Endurance, the specific capacity to stay under load and keep moving. The promise attached to it is receiving what was promised. Not now. After the enduring. The enduring comes first. What you need right now is not a better strategy. It is the willingness to not quit." },
    { v:"So do not throw away this confident trust in the Lord. Remember the great reward it brings you!", r:"Hebrews 10:35", d:"Me apobalete oun ten parreisian hemon, do not throw away your confidence. Apobalete: to throw away, to cast off, to discard. Paul knows the temptation is real, to take what has been built through faithfulness and throw it away in a moment of defeat. The great recompense, misthapodosia, a wage that is paid in return for work, is waiting. Hold what you have built. Even if you have to hold it with both hands today." },
    { v:"Blessed is the one who perseveres under trial because, having stood the test, that person will receive the crown of life.", r:"James 1:12", d:"Makarios, blessed, enviably fortunate, to be congratulated, is the word James uses for the one who endures under trial. Not the one who avoided the trial. Not the one who performed well when it was easy. The one who stayed under load and did not collapse. The crown of life goes to the one who loved God through the hard thing, not around it. If you are in the hard thing right now, you are in precisely the place where that crown is being prepared." },
    { v:"But as for you, be strong and courageous, for your work will be rewarded.", r:"2 Chronicles 15:7", d:"Chizqu v'al irpyu yadechem ki yesh sachar liflatchem, be strong and do not let your hands be weak, for there is a reward for your work. The reward exists. It is real. It is coming. And the condition for receiving it is not brilliance or speed. It is that your hands do not go slack. Work and do not lose heart. The reward is attached to the doing, not to the feeling." },
    { v:"So let's not get tired of doing what is good. At just the right time we will reap a harvest of blessing if we don't give up.", r:"Galatians 6:9", d:"Me enkakomen, do not lose heart, do not grow weary to the point of giving up. The verb describes a weariness that leads to quitting, not just to tiredness. Paul knows this is a real risk and names it. The promise attached to the not-quitting is a harvest at the right time, kairo idio, the season appointed by God, not the one you have decided is reasonable. The plant looks unchanged above ground for weeks and then the fruit appears. The faithfulness is in your hands. The timing is not." },
    { v:"I press on to reach the end of the race and receive the heavenly prize for which God is calling us.", r:"Philippians 3:14", d:"Kata skopon dioko, I press on toward the goal. Dioko: to pursue, to chase, to press after with urgency and intensity. Not jogging. Not drifting. Pressing forward with the full weight of intention. This is how you run the long middle of the race, not with the excitement of the beginning, but with the deliberate lean of someone who knows the finish line is real and the prize is worth every step of the pressing." },
    { v:"I have fought the good fight, I have finished the race, and I have remained faithful.", r:"2 Timothy 4:7", d:"Ton agona ton kalon egonismai, I have fought the good fight. Ton dromon teteleka, I have finished the course. Ten pistin teterekai, I have kept the faith. Three perfects, past actions with present effects. He fought, and the fight stands completed. He ran, and the race stands finished. He kept the faith, and the faith stands kept. Not the most impressive metrics. Not the most brilliant career. These three things. They are worth building toward." },
    { v:"And now the prize awaits me — the crown of righteousness.", r:"2 Timothy 4:8", d:"Apokeitai moi, laid up for me, stored away, waiting. The crown is already in place. It is being kept for the one who finishes. Paul's confidence is in the righteousness of the Judge, not in his own perfection. The crown is given to those who have loved his appearing, who lived in hopeful anticipation of what is coming. Let that expectation shape how you run today." },
    { v:"Work willingly at whatever you do, as though you were working for the Lord rather than for people.", r:"Colossians 3:23", d:"Ek psyches, from the soul, from the whole inner person, not from external compulsion or the desire to be seen. Work that is done from the soul has a different quality than work done for performance. The session no one will praise, the discipline no one witnesses, this is where the soul is formed. The Lord sees what happens in the unremarkable moments. Working for him rather than for people is a standard that does not require an audience." },
    { v:"Remember that the Lord will give you an inheritance as your reward, and that the Master you are serving is Christ.", r:"Colossians 3:24", d:"The development of endurance is a present-tense process, happening right now. The hard thing you are in is not a setback from the development. It is the mechanism of the development. Rejoice, not because it is easy, but because you can see what is being built in it." },
    { v:"But the one who endures to the end will be saved.", r:"Matthew 10:22", d:"Ho de hupomeinas eis telos houtos sothesetai, the one who endures to the end will be saved. To the end, eis telos. Not almost to the end. Not close to the end. To it. There is no prize for stopping near the finish. The race ends. The question is whether you are still running when it does. Endure to the end." },
    { v:"Remain faithful even when facing death, and I will give you the crown of life.", r:"Revelation 2:10", d:"Ginou pistos achri thanatou, be faithful until death. Not until it becomes convenient. Not until it stops costing something. Until death. The crown of life is not for the one who was faithful when it was easy. It is for the one who held on when they had every reason to let go. This is the kind of faithfulness worth building. Begin now, in the small things, so that the large ones do not surprise you." },
    { v:"I have told you all this so that you may have peace in me. Take heart, because I have overcome the world.", r:"John 16:33", d:"En to kosmo thlipsin exete, in the world you will have tribulation. Jesus does not promise otherwise. What he says is: I have overcome the world, nenikekai, perfect tense, already done, a completed act. The overcoming has already happened. The tribulation you face is real, but it is fighting against a victory that has already been won. You are not trying to win. You are living in the wake of a victory already secured. Take heart from that." },
    { v:"In the same way, let your good deeds shine out for all to see, so that everyone will praise your heavenly Father.", r:"Matthew 5:16", d:"Lampsato to phos hymon emprosthen ton anthropon, let your light shine before men. Hopos idosin hymon ta kala erga, so that they may see your good works. The light that shines is not dramatic. It is the consistent faithfulness that accumulates into something visible over time. The person who kept showing up, who kept caring for their body, who kept choosing the harder right thing, they become visible. Not because they advertised it. Because faithfulness is luminous." },
    { v:"We are pressed on every side by troubles, but we are not crushed. We get knocked down, but we are not destroyed.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:8–9", d:"When you are tempted to give up, look at what Jesus endured, not to shame yourself, but to gain perspective. He endured hostility, rejection, suffering, and death. And he did not quit. Whatever you are enduring today is survivable. Think of him. Then take the next step." },
    { v:"Those who trust in the Lord will find new strength. They will soar high on wings like eagles. They will run and not grow weary.", r:"Isaiah 40:31", d:"Qawe el Adonai yachlifu koach, those who wait on the Lord will renew their strength. Yachlifu: exchange, replace, get a fresh supply. Those who wait on God do not merely maintain their strength. They exchange the spent supply for a fresh one. They soar on wings as eagles. They run and do not grow weary. They walk and do not faint. All three speeds, the extraordinary and the ordinary, sustained by the same source." },
    { v:"For our struggle is not against flesh and blood, but against the rulers, against the powers of this dark world.", r:"Ephesians 6:12", d:"The deeds that shine are the consistent ones, the daily faithfulness that accumulates into something visible over time. Your training is one of those deeds. The health you steward, the energy you bring because you have invested in your body, these shine. People notice. And it points to something bigger than you." },
    { v:"I will keep on hoping for your help; I will praise you more and more.", r:"Psalm 71:14", d:"Keep on, a commitment renewed rather than a feeling sustained. Hope is the choice you make again in every ordinary day when circumstances are not cooperating. Praise that increases is the response of someone who has found that hope held. Let your praise grow in proportion to what God has sustained you through." },
    { v:"I can do everything through Christ, who gives me strength.", r:"Philippians 4:13", d:"Paul wrote this verse from a Roman prison, not from his greatest success. The context is a list of opposites he had learned to live inside: abundance and need, full stomach and hunger. The strength he describes is not something he had naturally. He learned it. The word ischuo, to be strong, describes strength given from outside yourself. It is not extra horsepower in your own engine. It is a different source entirely, one that does not depend on your circumstances being favorable." },
    { v:"Even when I walk through the darkest valley, I will not be afraid, for you are close beside me.", r:"Psalm 23:4", d:"Gam ki eileich b'gei tzalmavet lo ira ra ki attah imadi, even though I walk through the valley of the shadow of death, I will fear no evil, for you are with me. Imadi: with me, by my side, accompanying me. Not watching from a distance. Walking with you in the dark valley. The valley has a path through it, and someone who knows every valley is walking it beside you. You are not alone in the hard season." },
    { v:"Seek the Kingdom of God above all else, and live righteously, and he will give you everything you need.", r:"Matthew 6:33", d:"Jesus said this to people so anxious about food and clothing that he compared them to birds and flowers. His answer to that anxiety was not a better financial plan. It was a reordering of priority. When God is genuinely first, not first in theory, first in the actual decisions of your actual day, the anxiety changes shape. Not because the need goes away but because you are no longer carrying it alone. Seek the kingdom. Let the rest follow." },
    { v:"Patient endurance is what you need now, so that you will continue to do God's will. Then you will receive all that he has promised.", r:"Hebrews 10:36", d:"Hupomone gar humin chreian echete, for you have need of endurance. Not inspiration. Not intensity. Endurance, the specific capacity to stay under load and keep moving. The promise attached to it is receiving what was promised. Not now. After the enduring. The enduring comes first. What you need right now is not a better strategy. It is the willingness to not quit." },
  ],
  7: [
    { v:"So if the Son sets you free, you are truly free.", r:"John 8:36", d:"Ontos eleutheros esesthai, truly free you will be. Not somewhat free. Not legally free while feeling like a slave. Truly free, the word alethos, genuinely, actually, in the fullest sense of the word. The freedom Jesus offers is liberation of the interior person from the compulsion to earn, to perform, to manage the perception others have of you. You are free. The question is not whether this is true. The question is whether you are going to live from it." },
    { v:"You have been called to live in freedom. Use your freedom to serve one another in love.", r:"Galatians 5:13", d:"Ep eleutheria eklethete, you were called to freedom. Not freedom from all constraint. Freedom from the slavery of having to earn your standing. And then: dia tes agapes douleuete allelois, through love, serve one another. The freedom is purposeful. It was given so that the energy once consumed by self-management could be redirected toward love. You are free. Use the freedom for the thing it was designed for." },
    { v:"And you will know the truth, and the truth will set you free.", r:"John 8:32", d:"Ten aletheian gnosesthe kai he aletheia eleutherose humas, you will know the truth and the truth will free you. Gnosko: not merely intellectual knowledge but the kind that comes from personal encounter and experience. The truth that sets free is not a proposition you agree with from a distance. It is truth known from the inside. The truth about your body, that it is made by God, valued by God, worth caring for, known genuinely from the inside, produces freedom. Pursue that knowing." },
    { v:"Wherever the Spirit of the Lord is, there is freedom.", r:"2 Corinthians 3:17", d:"Hou de to pneuma kuriou, ekei eleutheria, where the Spirit of the Lord is, there is freedom. Wherever. The Spirit is not confined to spaces designated for spiritual things. He is present wherever you bring him. Invite him into your training, into the rest, into the way you think about your body and your progress. Freedom is not a state you achieve. It is a presence you receive and carry with you." },
    { v:"Many are the plans in a person's heart, but it is the Lord's purpose that prevails.", r:"Proverbs 19:21", d:"Rabboth machashavoth b'lev ish v'atzat Adonai hi taquom, many are the plans in a person's heart, but the purpose of the Lord will stand. Taquom: will rise, will stand firm, will prevail. You are allowed to plan. God does not dismiss your goals. But the purpose he has for you is more enduring than the plan you have made. When your plans and his purpose align, they have a solidity that ambition alone cannot produce. Hold your plans humbly." },
    { v:"The Lord will work out his plans for my life — for your faithful love, O Lord, endures forever.", r:"Psalm 138:8", d:"The Hebrew gamar means to complete, to finish, to bring to an end. It is the same word used for God completing creation. The Psalmist's confidence is not that his own efforts will finally pay off. It is that the God who began something in him will bring it to completion. The faithful love that drives this is olam, everlasting, without end, unconditional. On the days nothing works, on the weeks everything falls apart, his purpose for you is still in motion." },
    { v:"You didn't choose me. I chose you. I appointed you to go and produce lasting fruit.", r:"John 15:16", d:"The disciples did not go looking for Jesus. He found them at their fishing nets, at their tax tables, in the middle of their ordinary lives. The choosing was entirely his. He chose first. This is not a small point. It is the foundation of everything. You are not building a case for your own worth. You are responding to a selection that was already made. The fruit he calls you to produce grows from that security, not from the pressure to earn the choosing." },
    { v:"For we are his workmanship, created in Christ Jesus for good works, which God prepared beforehand.", r:"Ephesians 2:10", d:"The Greek word poema gives us the English word poem. You are God's poem, not his rough draft, not his unfinished project, not his ongoing repair work. A poem written by a master, every word chosen. Poems take time. They have revisions. What looks incomplete in the middle is part of the writing. The process you are in, the slow formation of body and character, is not evidence that you are unfinished. It is the nature of being carefully made." },
    { v:"If God is for us, who can ever be against us?", r:"Romans 8:31", d:"Ei ho theos hyper hemon, tis kath hemon, if God is for us, who can be against us? Paul does not say no one will oppose you. He says no one can prevail against you. There is a difference. The scale, the comparison, the voice that says you are not enough, these are real. But the God who is actively, personally for you, hyper hemon, exceeds all opposition. Stand on the reality of who is for you." },
    { v:"Since he did not spare even his own Son but gave him up for us all, won't he also give us everything else?", r:"Romans 8:32", d:"Hos ge tou idiou huiou ouk epheisato alla hyper panton hemon paredoken auton, he who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all. If he gave the most costly thing, the lesser things are not beyond his willingness to provide. The strength, the clarity, the self-discipline you need, these are not too much to ask from the God who gave his Son. Ask. The cross is the proof of his generosity." },
    { v:"I am the vine; you are the branches. Those who remain in me, and I in them, will produce much fruit.", r:"John 15:5", d:"Ego eimi he ampelos, I am the vine. Not a vine among many. The vine. And you are the branches, ta klimata. A branch has exactly one function: to remain connected to the vine and receive from it. Every fruit the branch produces comes through the connection, not from the branch itself. Whatever you are building, strength, discipline, health, flows from connection to Christ, not from straining alone. Remain in him. The fruit follows the remaining." },
    { v:"But if you remain in me and my words remain in you, you may ask for anything you want, and it will be granted!", r:"John 15:7", d:"Ean meinate en emoi kai ta remata mou en humin meintai, if you remain in me and my words remain in you. Both directions: you in him, his words in you. When both are true, the desires that form in you begin to align with what is good. The asking becomes trustworthy because it has been shaped by the Word. Remain. Let his words form your desires from the inside." },
    { v:"What does the Lord require of you? To act justly and to love mercy and to walk humbly with your God.", r:"Micah 6:8", d:"Hatzanea lechet im Eloheicha, to walk humbly with your God. Hatzanea: modestly, quietly, without drawing attention to yourself. Walk, lechet, a continuous, habitual walking. Not a sprint, not a moment. A sustained walking in the company of God through the ordinary days. The health you are building supports this walking, it gives you the embodied capacity to be present to what each ordinary day requires of you." },
    { v:"Love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind.", r:"Matthew 22:37", d:"Agapeseis kurion ton theon sou en hole te kardia sou, love the Lord your God with all your heart. All, holos, complete, entire, with nothing held back. Heart, soul, mind, each faculty offered completely. Training is one avenue of this offering. When you train as an act of love for the God who made this body and called it good, the motivation shifts from self-management to worship. Offer all of it." },
    { v:"Love your neighbor as yourself.", r:"Matthew 22:39", d:"Agapeseis ton plesion sou hos seauton, love your neighbor as yourself. Hos seauton: in the same way you care for yourself, with the same attentiveness and provision. The love of neighbor assumes a baseline of self-regard, not self-indulgence, but the kind of honest care that makes you capable of caring for someone else. Neglecting yourself is not humility. It is depletion. Care for yourself so you can pour from a full place." },
    { v:"For apart from me you can do nothing.", r:"John 15:5", d:"Ego eimi he ampelos, I am the vine. Not a vine among many. The vine. And you are the branches, ta klimata. A branch has exactly one function: to remain connected to the vine and receive from it. Every fruit the branch produces comes through the connection, not from the branch itself. Whatever you are building, strength, discipline, health, flows from connection to Christ, not from straining alone. Remain in him. The fruit follows the remaining." },
    { v:"God will generously provide all you need. Then you will always have everything you need and plenty left over to share with others.", r:"2 Corinthians 9:8", d:"Perisseuete eis pan ergon agathon, that you may abound in every good work. Perisseuete: overflow, have more than enough, be in surplus. God is not providing you with just enough for yourself. He has resourced you for overflow. The health and strength you are building is not merely for your own sustaining. It is capacity for the good work that overflows. What is the good work you are building capacity for?" },
    { v:"For I know the one in whom I trust, and I am sure that he is able to guard what I have entrusted to him.", r:"2 Timothy 1:12", d:"Oida gar o pepisteuka, I know whom I have believed. Person-based trust, not outcome-based. Paul trusts Christ, who he is, what he has done, what he has promised, not a particular result he is expecting. He is confident God can guard what has been entrusted to him. Hand over your body, your goals, your progress, your timeline. Trust the Keeper with the thing you care about most." },
    { v:"The Lord himself goes before you and will be with you; he will never leave you nor forsake you.", r:"Deuteronomy 31:8", d:"V'Adonai hu haholech l'faneicha, the Lord himself goes before you. V'hu yihyeh imach, he himself will be with you. Lo yarpecha v'lo ya'azbecha, he will not fail you or forsake you. Not a representation of God. Not a delegation. God himself. Going before, present with, refusing to fail or forsake. Whatever you are stepping into, it is not new territory to him. He has already been there." },
    { v:"Glory to God in highest heaven, and peace on earth to those with whom God is pleased.", r:"Luke 2:14", d:"Doxa en hupsistois theo, glory in the highest to God. Kai epi ges eirene en anthropois eudokias, and on earth peace among people of his good pleasure. Eirene: shalom, not the absence of conflict but the presence of everything in its right place. This is what the incarnation brings, not an escape from the world but the arrival of wholeness into it. The glory goes upward. The peace comes down. Receive what has come down." },
    { v:"When you did it to one of the least of these my brothers and sisters, you were doing it to me.", r:"Matthew 25:40", d:"As yourself, the love of neighbor requires a baseline of healthy self-regard. The kind of care for yourself that makes genuine care for others possible. Care for yourself as you would want to care for the person you love most. Then pour that overflow into them." },
    { v:"Live as people who are free, not using your freedom as a cover-up for evil, but living as servants of God.", r:"1 Peter 2:16", d:"Called, intentionally, specifically, personally. Before you earned it, before you deserved it, this was his plan. You are walking in a purpose older than you are. Let that settle the question of whether you belong here, whether you are doing enough, whether it is worth it." },
    { v:"I am leaving you with a gift — peace of mind and heart. The peace I give is a gift the world cannot give.", r:"John 14:27", d:"Eirenen aphiemi humin, peace I leave with you. Eirenen ten emen didomi humin, my peace I give you. Not as the world gives, ou kathos ho kosmos didosin. The world gives peace when circumstances cooperate. Christ gives peace that operates inside the circumstances that do not cooperate. When the results are not there, when the season is long, when the hard thing will not resolve, this peace was given at the cross. It is still available." },
    { v:"Whatever you do or say, do it as a representative of the Lord Jesus, giving thanks through him to God the Father.", r:"Colossians 3:17", d:"Panta en onomati kuriou Iesou, all things in the name of the Lord Jesus. All: every rep, every session, every decision about rest or nutrition. Carried in his name means done as a representative of who he is. What you do in his name should be something you are glad to carry his name into. Because whether you are aware of it or not, you do." },
    { v:"Work willingly at whatever you do, as though you were working for the Lord rather than for people.", r:"Colossians 3:23", d:"Ek psyches, from the soul, from the whole inner person, not from external compulsion or the desire to be seen. Work that is done from the soul has a different quality than work done for performance. The session no one will praise, the discipline no one witnesses, this is where the soul is formed. The Lord sees what happens in the unremarkable moments. Working for him rather than for people is a standard that does not require an audience." },
    { v:"God saved us and called us to live a holy life — not because we deserved it, but because that was his plan.", r:"2 Timothy 1:9", d:"Not according to our works, ouk kata ta erga hemon. The calling was issued before the works existed. You were called holy and set apart not because of what you would accomplish but because of God's own purpose and grace given before time began. You are walking in a purpose older than your existence. The question of whether you belong here was settled before you were born." },
    { v:"You made all the delicate, inner parts of my body and knit me together in my mother's womb.", r:"Psalm 139:13", d:"The Hebrew qanah means to acquire, to create, to possess, the word used when something is made with great care and then owned with great intentionality. God did not assemble you from a template. He created and possesses every inner part of you. The specific way you are made, the particular strengths, the specific limitations, the exact body you inhabit, was knit together with the same intention he gives to everything he makes. You are not an accident of biology." },
    { v:"Seek the Kingdom of God above all else, and live righteously, and he will give you everything you need.", r:"Matthew 6:33", d:"Jesus said this to people so anxious about food and clothing that he compared them to birds and flowers. His answer to that anxiety was not a better financial plan. It was a reordering of priority. When God is genuinely first, not first in theory, first in the actual decisions of your actual day, the anxiety changes shape. Not because the need goes away but because you are no longer carrying it alone. Seek the kingdom. Let the rest follow." },
    { v:"For this is how God loved the world: He gave his one and only Son, so that everyone who believes in him will not perish but have eternal life.", r:"John 3:16", d:"Houtos gar egapesen ho theos ton kosmon, God so loved the world. Edoken, he gave, he donated, he offered at cost. His one and only Son. Not a concept of giving. An actual, costly, irreversible act. For you, not the idealized version, not the version that has it together, you as you actually are. This is the foundation on which everything else stands. It is not shaken by your performance." },
    { v:"So be strong and courageous! Do not be afraid and do not panic. For the Lord your God will personally go ahead of you.", r:"Deuteronomy 31:6", d:"Moses said these words to Joshua on the edge of Canaan, knowing he himself would not cross over. He was not promising easy victory. He was promising divine presence inside the fight. The courage he calls for is not the kind that comes from confidence in yourself. It is the kind that becomes possible when you know who goes with you. What you are walking into is not new territory to God. He is already there, and he will not leave when it gets hard." },
    { v:"I am the vine; you are the branches. Those who remain in me will produce much fruit. For apart from me you can do nothing.", r:"John 15:5", d:"Ego eimi he ampelos, I am the vine. Not a vine among many. The vine. And you are the branches, ta klimata. A branch has exactly one function: to remain connected to the vine and receive from it. Every fruit the branch produces comes through the connection, not from the branch itself. Whatever you are building, strength, discipline, health, flows from connection to Christ, not from straining alone. Remain in him. The fruit follows the remaining." },
  ],
  8: [
    { v:"Don't you realize that your body is the temple of the Holy Spirit, who lives in you and was given to you by God? You do not belong to yourself.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:19", d:"Naos tou en humin hagiou pneumatos estin, your body is the temple of the Holy Spirit who is in you. Naos: the inner sanctuary, the Holy of Holies, the place where the presence of God dwells. Not the outer courts. The innermost place. That is what Paul calls your body. The implications are not small. If the Spirit of God has taken up residence in your body, then the care of your body is not a vanity project. It is the stewardship of a dwelling place." },
    { v:"For God bought you with a high price. So you must honor God with your body.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:20", d:"Egoresthete gar times, you were bought with a price. Times: of great worth, at great cost. The cost was the life of the Son of God. That transaction changes the nature of the ownership. Your body is not fully yours to do with as you please. It belongs to the One who paid for it. Doxasate de ton theon en to somati humon, glorify God in your body. This is not a burden. It is the appropriate response to having been purchased at infinite cost." },
    { v:"So whether you eat or drink, or whatever you do, do it all for the glory of God.", r:"1 Corinthians 10:31", d:"Panta eis doxan theou poieite, do all things for the glory of God. Panta: all, every, without exception. The session that feels ordinary. The meal that is unremarkable. The sleep that seems too mundane to matter. All of it is territory for glory. Not by making it dramatic but by making it intentional and offered. The mundane choices are where most of the glory actually happens." },
    { v:"Dear friend, I hope all is well with you and that you are as healthy in body as you are strong in spirit.", r:"3 John 1:2", d:"Peri panton euchomai se euodousthai kai hugiainein, I pray that in all things you may prosper and be in good health. Hugiainein: to be healthy, to be sound, to be well. John prays for physical health alongside the health of the soul. These are not separate domains for him. The body and soul are partners in the whole person. The same intentionality you bring to your spiritual life belongs in the care of your body." },
    { v:"Physical training is good, but training for godliness is much better, promising benefits in this life and in the life to come.", r:"1 Timothy 4:8", d:"He somatike askesis pros oligon estin ophelimos, bodily training is profitable for a little. Paul does not dismiss it. He calls it ophelimos, useful, beneficial, of value. And training for godliness is profitable for all things, pros panta. Both are called profitable. The body is good stewardship of something temporary. Godliness is stewardship of something permanent. Build both. Let one serve the other." },
    { v:"So let the Holy Spirit guide your lives. Then you won't be doing what your sinful nature craves.", r:"Galatians 5:16", d:"Pneumati peripatei te, walk by the Spirit. Peripateo: to walk, to live, to conduct your daily life. The Spirit leads in the daily, embodied decisions, not just in the obviously spiritual ones. He is available in the question of what to eat, when to rest, how to move. The Spirit-led approach to your body is one of discernment: what does this body actually need today? Ask him. That wisdom is available." },
    { v:"Give your bodies to God because of all he has done for you. Let them be a living and holy sacrifice — the kind he will find acceptable.", r:"Romans 12:1", d:"Parasastai ta somata humon thusian zosan hagian, present your bodies as a living sacrifice, holy. Zosan: living, alive, active. Not dead on an altar. Offered while still breathing. The offering is daily, embodied, made through the specific choices of an ordinary life. Every session, every meal, every decision about rest, this is the sacrifice. Your body is what you bring. Bring it." },
    { v:"Don't let the world around you squeeze you into its own mold, but let God re-make you so that your whole attitude of mind is changed.", r:"Romans 12:2", d:"The Greek metamorphoo, from which we get metamorphosis, describes transformation at the level of form, not just behavior. Paul says this happens by the renewing of your mind: anakainosis, a complete renovation from the inside. The world has a script about what bodies are for, what gives them value, what makes them acceptable. That script is written in you whether you know it or not. Transformation begins when God rewrites it. Ask him to start there." },
    { v:"The human body has many parts, but the many parts make up one whole body.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:12", d:"Kathos gar to soma hen estin kai mele polla echei, just as the body is one and has many members. The body is one organism with many parts, each serving the others. Neglect one part and every other part eventually suffers. Neglect mobility and strength declines. Neglect sleep and recovery fails. Neglect deep stabilizers and the joints give out. The body is designed for wholeness. Train the whole person." },
    { v:"God has put each part just where he wants it.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:18", d:"Nun de ho theos etheto ta mele, God placed the members. Placed, etheto, set in position, arranged intentionally. Your body in its specific configuration was not a random outcome. The particular strengths and limitations you have were placed by God. The limitation that frustrates you may be exactly what shapes the character you most need. Do not demand a different body. Steward the one you were given." },
    { v:"Some parts of the body that seem weakest and least important are actually the most necessary.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:22", d:"Alla polu mallon ta dokounta mele tou somatos asthenesteron hyparchein anagkaia estin, the parts that seem weaker are actually necessary. Anagkaia: necessary, indispensable, not merely useful. The deep stabilizers no one sees, the recovery work no one measures, the sleep no one applauds, these are doing some of the most essential work. The things that seem minor often carry the most. Do not skip what seems unimportant." },
    { v:"All of you together are Christ's body, and each of you is a part of it.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:27", d:"Energetic, strong, a hard worker, this is the description of the woman who fears God. Not primarily aesthetic but functional. She has the energy and strength to do what she is called to do. This is the purpose of physical training: not appearance but capability. Build the energy and strength to be the person God has called you to be." },
    { v:"I praise you because I am fearfully and wonderfully made; your works are wonderful, I know that full well.", r:"Psalm 139:14", d:"The Hebrew pala, wonderful, set apart, distinguished from everything ordinary, is the word David uses for what God has made him to be. He does not say this after looking in a mirror and feeling good about what he sees. He says it as a theological statement about what he knows to be true about his maker. The body you are in right now was made with the same deliberate attention God gave to the rest of creation. Worship is the appropriate response. Not critique." },
    { v:"She is energetic and strong, a hard worker.", r:"Proverbs 31:17", d:"Chagara b'oz motneiha vatamets zero'oteiha, she girds herself with strength and makes her arms strong. The Proverbs 31 woman is described in terms of what she can do, not how she looks. Strength for the task. Energy for the work. Capability for the calling. This is the purpose of physical training: not appearance but functional capacity for the life you are called to live. Build the strength to do what you are called to do." },
    { v:"She watches over the affairs of her household and does not eat the bread of idleness.", r:"Proverbs 31:27", d:"Tzofiah halichot beita v'lechem atzlut lo tochal, she looks well to the ways of her household and does not eat the bread of idleness. Idleness, atzlut, laziness, the habit of doing nothing when something is needed. She does not eat that bread. Not because she is driven or anxious. Because she is present and attentive to what is required of her each day. The daily tending, unremarkable, consistent, faithful, is the substance of her life." },
    { v:"Lazy people want much but get little, but those who work hard will prosper.", r:"Proverbs 13:4", d:"Nefesh atzlan mit'avah v'ayin, the soul of the sluggard craves and gets nothing. V'nefesh charutzim tedushan, the soul of the diligent is richly supplied. The parallel is exact: craving without working, working and receiving abundance. The appetite for health, for strength, for a body that functions well, these desires are worth working for. The diligent soul gets what it works toward. Work." },
    { v:"Work brings profit, but mere talk leads to poverty!", r:"Proverbs 14:23", d:"B'chol etzev yihyeh motar, in all toil there is profit. Toil, etzev, the hard work that costs something. There is motar in it, surplus, advantage, gain. But mere talk, dvar sfatayim, leads to lack. The planning without the doing. The intending without the session. All of it is talk until you show up. The profit exists in the work itself. You already know what to do." },
    { v:"Whatever you do, work at it with all your heart, as working for the Lord, not for human masters.", r:"Colossians 3:23", d:"Ek psyches, from the soul, from the whole inner person, not from external compulsion or the desire to be seen. Work that is done from the soul has a different quality than work done for performance. The session no one will praise, the discipline no one witnesses, this is where the soul is formed. The Lord sees what happens in the unremarkable moments. Working for him rather than for people is a standard that does not require an audience." },
    { v:"A peaceful heart leads to a healthy body; jealousy is like cancer in the bones.", r:"Proverbs 14:30", d:"Lev marpe chaim basar, a heart of healing is life to the body. Marpe: health, healing, tranquility of spirit. The Hebrew connects the state of the inner person directly to the health of the outer body. This is not metaphor. The cortisol of chronic anxiety, the physical cost of sustained contempt for yourself, these have measurable effects on the body. Tend the interior. It will show in the body over time." },
    { v:"Kind words are like honey — sweet to the soul and healthy for the body.", r:"Proverbs 16:24", d:"Tzuf dvash imrei noam, pleasant words are a honeycomb. Metuq l'nefesh umarpeh l'atzem, sweet to the soul and healing to the body. Including the words you speak to yourself. The internal monologue about your body, your progress, your limitations, this is speech that either builds or corrodes. Speak to yourself with the same words you would offer to someone whose body is worth caring for. Because it is." },
    { v:"Don't be deceived: God cannot be mocked. A man reaps what he sows.", r:"Galatians 6:7", d:"Ha theos ou mukterizatai, God is not mocked. The word mukterizatai describes turning your nose up at something, treating it with contempt. You cannot treat the principle of sowing and reaping with contempt and escape the consequences. The harvest follows the sowing, not as punishment, but as the operation of the way God designed things to work. Sow faithfully. The harvest follows." },
    { v:"Those who live to please the Spirit will harvest everlasting life.", r:"Galatians 6:8", d:"The one who sows to the Spirit will from the Spirit reap eternal life, zoe aionios, the life of the age to come, life that is qualitatively different and permanent. Sowing and reaping is not a metaphor for magic. It is a description of how reality works in God's design. The consistent choices that honor the Spirit, showing up, choosing nourishment over punishment, building rather than eroding, produce a harvest. Not immediately. But reliably." },
    { v:"The Lord nurses them when they are sick and restores them to health.", r:"Psalm 41:3", d:"Adonai yis'adenu al eres duvai, the Lord sustains him on his sickbed. Yis'adenu: to support, to prop up, to lay a foundation under. God is present in the injury, in the illness, in the recovery, in the body that will not cooperate. He is not absent from the process. He is the support beneath it. Trust the manner and the timing of his healing to him." },
    { v:"He heals the brokenhearted and bandages their wounds.", r:"Psalm 147:3", d:"Haro'fe lishvurei lev umechabesh le'atzvotam, he heals the brokenhearted and binds up their wounds. Mechabesh: to wrap, to bandage, to bind with careful, skilled attention. The image is of a healer who knows exactly where the wound is and wraps it with competence and care. He is not treating a general condition. He is bandaging your specific wound. Bring it to him specifically." },
    { v:"I discipline my body like an athlete, training it to do what it should.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:27", d:"Hupopiazo mou to soma, I discipline my body, I treat it roughly, I bring it under control. And doulagogo, I make it my slave, I bring it into submission. Paul takes the possibility of disqualification seriously enough to train his body with intentionality. The message he carried and the life he lived had to be coherent. The same is true for you. Your private discipline either aligns with or contradicts who you say you are." },
    { v:"And I will put a new spirit in you. I will take out your stony, stubborn heart and give you a tender, responsive heart.", r:"Ezekiel 36:26", d:"V'natati lachem lev chadash v'ruach chadasha eten b'qirb'chem, I will give you a new heart and put a new spirit within you. Chadash: new, fresh, something that was not there before. Not a reformed heart. Not an improved version. New. The old patterns, the old compulsions, the old relationship with your body, these do not have to be overcome by willpower. They can be replaced from the inside. Ask for the new heart. Everything else grows from it." },
    { v:"All athletes are disciplined in their training. They do it to win a prize that will fade away, but we do it for an eternal prize.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:25", d:"Pas ho agonizomenos panta egkrateuetai, every athlete exercises self-control in all things. All things, not the things he feels like controlling. All. The one who trains for a prize that will rust shows more discipline than most people ever summon. And you are training for something that does not rust. Let the eternal prize motivate a deeper and more sustained discipline than any temporary reward could produce." },
    { v:"We are being transformed into his image with ever-increasing glory.", r:"2 Corinthians 3:18", d:"Katoptrizomenoi, beholding as in a mirror, reflecting back. And metamorphoumetha, being transformed, metamorphosing, changing at the level of form. Both verbs are present passive: happening now, being done to you, not by you. You become what you behold. If you fix your sustained attention on Christ, his patience, his faithfulness, his refusal to quit, those qualities form in you not through striving but through looking. The looking is the practice." },
    { v:"Do you not know that your body is the temple of the Holy Spirit? Therefore honor God with your body.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:19", d:"Naos tou en humin hagiou pneumatos estin, your body is the temple of the Holy Spirit who is in you. Naos: the inner sanctuary, the Holy of Holies, the place where the presence of God dwells. Not the outer courts. The innermost place. That is what Paul calls your body. The implications are not small. If the Spirit of God has taken up residence in your body, then the care of your body is not a vanity project. It is the stewardship of a dwelling place." },
    { v:"So let the Holy Spirit guide your lives.", r:"Galatians 5:16", d:"Pneumati peripatei te, walk by the Spirit. Peripateo: to walk, to live, to conduct your daily life. The Spirit leads in the daily, embodied decisions, not just in the obviously spiritual ones. He is available in the question of what to eat, when to rest, how to move. The Spirit-led approach to your body is one of discernment: what does this body actually need today? Ask him. That wisdom is available." },
    { v:"For God bought you with a high price. So you must honor God with your body.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:20", d:"Egoresthete gar times, you were bought with a price. Times: of great worth, at great cost. The cost was the life of the Son of God. That transaction changes the nature of the ownership. Your body is not fully yours to do with as you please. It belongs to the One who paid for it. Doxasate de ton theon en to somati humon, glorify God in your body. This is not a burden. It is the appropriate response to having been purchased at infinite cost." },
  ],
  9: [
    { v:"For God has not given us a spirit of fear and timidity, but of power, love, and self-discipline.", r:"2 Timothy 1:7", d:"The three gifts Paul names, power, love, and self-discipline, come from the same source and arrive together. The self-discipline in this verse is sophronismos: soundness of mind, sober judgment, the ability to govern yourself wisely. It is not white-knuckled willpower. It flows from the same place as power and love, and it is described as a gift of the Spirit. The person who asks for it and then acts as if they received it will find it growing." },
    { v:"I discipline my body like an athlete, training it to do what it should.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:27", d:"Hupopiazo mou to soma, I discipline my body, I treat it roughly, I bring it under control. And doulagogo, I make it my slave, I bring it into submission. Paul takes the possibility of disqualification seriously enough to train his body with intentionality. The message he carried and the life he lived had to be coherent. The same is true for you. Your private discipline either aligns with or contradicts who you say you are." },
    { v:"No discipline is enjoyable while it is happening — it's painful! But afterward there will be a peaceful harvest of right living.", r:"Hebrews 12:11", d:"The author uses the word paideian, training, discipline, the education of a child by a parent. Not punishment. Formation. And he does not soften what it feels like in the moment: painful, not joyful. But the afterward, the peaceable fruit of righteousness, is what he fixes your attention on. Not the pain of the present process but the harvest on the other side of it. The harvest cannot come without the process. Stay in it." },
    { v:"For the Lord corrects those he loves, just as a father corrects a child in whom he delights.", r:"Proverbs 3:12", d:"Discipline from a loving God looks different from punishment from an indifferent authority. It is targeted, purposeful, motivated by love. When something needs to change, when progress stalls, when patterns need addressing, receive it as correction from a Father, not condemnation from a judge." },
    { v:"Don't reject the Lord's discipline, and don't be upset when he corrects you.", r:"Proverbs 3:11", d:"Do not reject the discipline. The temptation is to get defensive, to minimize, to explain away what God is correcting. The path forward is through, not around. Receive the correction. The Lord corrects those he loves, which means correction is evidence of his care, not his disappointment." },
    { v:"Look straight ahead, and fix your eyes on what lies before you.", r:"Proverbs 4:25", d:"The instruction is physically specific. Eyes forward. Not left, not right, not behind. The Proverbs describe comparison as one of the most reliable roads away from the life you are meant to live. Someone else's progress is not your measurement. Their timeline is not your deadline. The next step in front of you is all you need to see right now. Look at it. Take it." },
    { v:"Mark out a straight path for your feet; stay on the safe path.", r:"Proverbs 4:26", d:"Palles ma'agal raglecha v'chol deracheicha yikonu, ponder the path for your feet and let all your ways be established. Palles: to weigh, to make level, to examine carefully. Not wandering in the general direction of good intentions. Deliberate examination of the path and deliberate walking of it. Mark out where you are going and how you intend to get there. Then stay on it." },
    { v:"Don't get sidetracked; keep your feet from following evil.", r:"Proverbs 4:27", d:"Al taseit yamin usmol, do not turn to the right or to the left. The deviations that accumulate into a different life are rarely dramatic. One skipped session becomes two. One compromised choice establishes a pattern. The subtle drift is more dangerous than the obvious detour because it does not announce itself. Stay on the path you deliberately marked out." },
    { v:"We capture their rebellious thoughts and teach them to obey Christ.", r:"2 Corinthians 10:5", d:"Aichmalotizontes pan noema eis ten hypakoen tou Christou, taking every thought captive to the obedience of Christ. Aichmalotizontes: to capture as a prisoner of war, to seize and subdue. The thoughts about your body that run unchecked, comparison, shame, contempt, can be seized and brought under the authority of what is actually true. Every time you replace a lie with truth, you are doing real warfare in the place it matters most." },
    { v:"Fix your thoughts on what is true, and honorable, and right, and pure, and lovely, and admirable.", r:"Philippians 4:8", d:"Hosa estin alethes, whatever is true. Hosa semnon, honorable. Hosa dikaia, just. Hosa hagna, pure. Hosa prosphile, lovely. Hosa euphema, commendable. Paul gives a specific inventory of what to think about. This is not positive thinking. It is truth-anchored thinking, deliberate attention given to what is actually real. What you sustain your attention on shapes you. Fix it on what is true." },
    { v:"Think about things that are excellent and worthy of praise.", r:"Philippians 4:8", d:"Hosa estin alethes, whatever is true. Hosa semnon, honorable. Hosa dikaia, just. Hosa hagna, pure. Hosa prosphile, lovely. Hosa euphema, commendable. Paul gives a specific inventory of what to think about. This is not positive thinking. It is truth-anchored thinking, deliberate attention given to what is actually real. What you sustain your attention on shapes you. Fix it on what is true." },
    { v:"Don't worry about anything; instead, pray about everything. Tell God what you need, and thank him for all he has done.", r:"Philippians 4:6", d:"Me merimnate, do not be anxious. About anything, peri medenos. Instead, alla, in everything, en panti, by prayer and supplication with thanksgiving, proseuche kai deesis met eucharistias, let your requests be known to God. The anxiety has somewhere to go. It does not have to stay. Redirect it into prayer, every specific concern, named and offered. This is the practice of trust built one redirected worry at a time." },
    { v:"Then you will experience God's peace, which exceeds anything we can understand.", r:"Philippians 4:7", d:"God's peace exceeds understanding, it does not require favorable circumstances to operate. This is the peace available in the middle of a hard training season, a slow week, a body that will not cooperate. It is not produced by getting everything right. It is given. Ask for the guard to be posted." },
    { v:"His peace will guard your hearts and minds as you live in Christ Jesus.", r:"Philippians 4:7", d:"His peace guards your heart and mind, it stands between you and the anxiety that would otherwise invade. This is not passive: you ask for it, receive it, let it guard. The guard is already available. Position yourself to receive it." },
    { v:"So humble yourselves before God. Resist the devil, and he will flee from you.", r:"James 4:7", d:"Antistete to diabolo kai pheuxetai aph humon, resist the devil and he will flee from you. Antistete: to take a position against, to stand in opposition, to actively resist. Not passive avoidance. Active, deliberate resistance. Push back against the voice of shame, the comparison spiral, the temptation to quit. The promise is that resistance causes flight. The enemy does not stay where he is resisted. Stand firm." },
    { v:"Come close to God, and God will come close to you.", r:"James 4:8", d:"Engisate to theo kai engisei humin, draw near to God and he will draw near to you. Engisate: move toward, come close, approach. The distance between you and God is not fixed. You move toward him. He moves toward you. The movement is mutual and it is always available. In the gym, on the rest day, in the middle of the hard week, draw close. He is coming toward those who come toward him." },
    { v:"Humble yourselves before the Lord, and he will lift you up in honor.", r:"James 4:10", d:"Tapeinothete enopion kuriou kai hupsoo humas, humble yourself before the Lord and he will exalt you. Tapeinothete: to make yourself low, to accept a lower position. Humility in practice means accepting where you actually are instead of where you think you should be. That acceptance, of your actual current state, with no inflation, is the beginning of genuine progress. God exalts the humble. He does not exalt the performance of humility." },
    { v:"Stay alert! Watch out for your great enemy, the devil. He prowls around like a roaring lion, looking for someone to devour.", r:"1 Peter 5:8", d:"Nepstate gregoresate, be sober and watchful. Ho antidikos hymon diabolos hos leon oruomenos peripatei, your adversary the devil walks around like a roaring lion seeking whom he may devour. The image is of an active threat that moves, that watches for the unguarded moment. Watchfulness requires awareness that you are in a real contest. Name the voices that diminish you. Resist them. They are real but they are not all-powerful." },
    { v:"Stand firm against him, and be strong in your faith.", r:"1 Peter 5:9", d:"Ho antistete stereoi te pistei, resist him, firm in the faith. Stereoi: solid, hard, unyielding under pressure. The faith you stand in is the specific knowledge of what is true: you are loved, held, working toward something real, accompanied by someone who does not leave. Stand on that when the opposition is real and the pressure is high. The standing is the act of faith." },
    { v:"After you have suffered a little while, he will restore, support, and strengthen you, and place you on a firm foundation.", r:"1 Peter 5:10", d:"Katartizo, to repair, to restore to proper order, to mend what was broken. Sterizo, to set firmly, to establish with unshakeable stability. Stheoo, to strengthen, to make strong. All three of these are things God does, not things you accomplish. After the suffering, which is real and which he does not minimize, God acts. The foundation being set beneath you is set by hands stronger than yours. Trust the builder with the building." },
    { v:"We should live in this evil world with wisdom, righteousness, and devotion to God.", r:"Titus 2:12", d:"Sophronos kai dikaios kai eusebos zesomen en to nun aioni, we may live soberly, righteously, and godly in the present age. Three adverbs describing how to live: soberly, sophronos, with sound judgment. Righteously, dikaios, in right relationship with God and others. Godly, eusebos, with reverence and devotion. All three together. Not one at the expense of the others. Train wisely. Choose righteously. Devote the whole thing to God." },
    { v:"Let everything you say be good and helpful, so that your words will be an encouragement to those who hear them.", r:"Ephesians 4:29", d:"Pas logos sapros ek tou stomatos hymon me ekporeuesthoo, let no corrupting talk come out of your mouth. Sapros: rotten, worthless, that which destroys rather than builds. Including what you say to yourself. The internal speech about your body, your progress, your limitations, this is real speech with real effects. Let it be agathos pros oikodomenos, good for building up. Speak to yourself as you would speak to someone whose body is worth caring for." },
    { v:"Get rid of all bitterness, rage, anger, harsh words, and slander.", r:"Ephesians 4:31", d:"Pasa pikria kai thumos kai orge kai krauge kai blasphemia artheto aph' humon, let all bitterness, wrath, anger, clamor, and slander be put away from you. Artheto: lifted up and removed, taken away and carried off. Including bitterness toward yourself, the harsh self-judgment, the contempt for where you are. These are forms of pikria that corrode from the inside. Remove them. Not by pretending they are not there, but by releasing what is not serving your formation." },
    { v:"Instead, be kind to each other, tenderhearted, forgiving one another, just as God through Christ has forgiven you.", r:"Ephesians 4:32", d:"Ginesthe de eis allelous chrestoi, be kind to one another. Eusplanchnoi, tenderhearted, compassionate. Charidzomenoi heautois, forgiving one another. The forgiveness you receive from God can be applied inward, forgiving yourself for missed sessions, poor choices, the gap between intention and action. Tenderness toward yourself is not self-indulgence. It is the application of the gospel to your own interior life." },
    { v:"Imitate God, therefore, in everything you do, because you are his dear children.", r:"Ephesians 5:1", d:"Ginesthe oun mimetai tou theou, be imitators of God. Hos tekna agapeta, as beloved children. Children imitate the parent they love. God is patient with growth that takes time. He is consistent in his attention. He does not give up. Imitate that. Be patient with your own growth. Stay consistent in the attention you give to becoming who you are called to be." },
    { v:"For once you were full of darkness, but now you have light from the Lord. So live as people of light!", r:"Ephesians 5:8", d:"Nun de phos en kurio, now you are light in the Lord. Hos tekna photos peripatei te, walk as children of light. The darkness of shame, self-contempt, the belief that you are not worth caring for, that is not your home. Phos: light, radiance, the source of illumination. You are light in the Lord. Live from that identity in the practical, embodied decisions of your actual day." },
    { v:"Warn each other every day, while it is still today, so that none of you will be deceived by sin and hardened against God.", r:"Hebrews 3:13", d:"Today, semeron, this specific day, while it is still called today. The writer knows that hardness does not arrive all at once. It sets in gradually, through small daily neglects, through the slow accumulation of unremarkable choices that bend the heart away from God. The antidote is the same: daily, current, specific encouragement. Not eventually. Today. Tend the relationships that speak truth to you. Do not let the drift go unaddressed." },
    { v:"Since he did not spare even his own Son, won't he also give us everything else?", r:"Romans 8:32", d:"Hos ge tou idiou huiou ouk epheisato alla hyper panton hemon paredoken auton, he who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all. If he gave the most costly thing, the lesser things are not beyond his willingness to provide. The strength, the clarity, the self-discipline you need, these are not too much to ask from the God who gave his Son. Ask. The cross is the proof of his generosity." },
    { v:"Teach the older men to exercise self-control, to be worthy of respect, and to live wisely.", r:"Titus 2:2", d:"Presbutas nephaliou einai, older men are to be sober-minded. Semnous, dignified. Sophronas, self-controlled. The self-control described here is not grim or harsh. It is semnos, dignified, worthy of respect, marked by a gravity that comes from having decided what matters. Not white-knuckling. The quiet consistency of someone who has decided. Build toward that kind of self-discipline: the kind that looks settled, not strained." },
    { v:"Commit your actions to the Lord, and your plans will succeed.", r:"Proverbs 16:3", d:"The Hebrew word galal means to roll, to heave a heavy thing onto something stronger. You are not asked to hand your plans gently to God. You are asked to roll them off your shoulders onto his, the way you would roll a boulder you cannot carry. You still make the plan. You still do the work. But the outcome and the timing are his to hold, not yours. The person who does this finds that the anxiety of striving is replaced by something steadier." },
  ],
  10: [
    { v:"Give thanks to the Lord, for he is good! His faithful love endures forever.", r:"Psalm 107:1", d:"Hodu l'Adonai ki tov, give thanks to the Lord for he is good. Ki l'olam chasdo, for his steadfast love endures forever. The reason for thanksgiving is not circumstances. It is character. Tov: good, in the deepest sense, intrinsically good. Chasdo: covenant love, faithful love, the love that does not terminate. Gratitude rooted in who God is rather than in how things are going is the only kind that holds in every season." },
    { v:"Always be joyful. Never stop praying. Be thankful in all circumstances.", r:"1 Thessalonians 5:16–18", d:"En panti eucharistei te, in everything give thanks. Not for everything. In everything, inside whatever is happening, while it is happening, without waiting for it to resolve. This is not denial. It is the deliberate choice of a posture that acknowledges God's presence inside the circumstances rather than only after them. Thanksgiving in difficulty is a spiritual discipline. It is also one of the most countercultural acts available." },
    { v:"Give thanks for everything to God the Father in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.", r:"Ephesians 5:20", d:"Eucharistountes pantote hyper panton, giving thanks always for all things. Always. For all things. The body that showed up today. The capacity to move. The breath that was there for one more rep. The rest that restored what was depleted. Every ordinary good is from the same God who gave the extraordinary ones. Notice them. Name them. Give thanks for the ones you are usually too busy to see." },
    { v:"Enter his gates with thanksgiving; go into his courts with praise. Give thanks to him and praise his name.", r:"Psalm 100:4", d:"Bou sho'arav b'todah, enter his gates with thanksgiving. Chatzerotav bit'hilah, his courts with praise. You do not earn access to God's presence. You receive it. Todah: thanksgiving, gratitude, the acknowledgment of a gift received. The posture for entering his presence is not performance. It is the recognition that you are there because of what he has done, not what you have done. Bring that posture to everything today." },
    { v:"For the Lord is good. His unfailing love continues forever, and his faithfulness continues to each generation.", r:"Psalm 100:5", d:"Ki tov Adonai l'olam chasdo, for the Lord is good; his steadfast love endures forever. V'ad dor vador emunatho, his faithfulness to all generations. Faithfulness, emunat, to all generations. Not just to yours when you are consistent. To every generation, in every season, regardless of the circumstances they are in. The faithfulness is not conditional. Build your gratitude on what does not change." },
    { v:"I will praise you, Lord, with all my heart; I will tell of all the marvelous things you have done.", r:"Psalm 9:1", d:"Odeh Adonai b'chol libi, I will give thanks to the Lord with all my heart. Asapra kol nifl'oteicha, I will tell of all your wondrous works. All, kol. Not the highlights. All of them. The recovery from the injury you thought would not heal. The day you did not think you could finish but did. The unexpected energy that arrived when the tank seemed empty. Count them. Tell them. Specific gratitude is the most powerful kind." },
    { v:"Let all that I am praise the Lord; with my whole heart, I will praise his holy name.", r:"Psalm 103:1", d:"Barchi nafshi et Adonai v'chol qaravai et shem qodsho, bless the Lord, O my soul, and all that is within me, bless his holy name. All that is within you, the tired parts, the frustrated parts, the parts that are not sure the effort is working. All of it can be turned toward God in praise. Wholehearted blessing is not the performance of enthusiasm. It is the turning of the full self, exactly as it is, toward God." },
    { v:"Let all that I am praise the Lord; may I never forget the good things he does for me.", r:"Psalm 103:2", d:"Barchi nafshi et Adonai v'al tishkichi kol g'mulav, bless the Lord, O my soul, and forget none of his benefits. Al tishkichi: do not forget. The command against forgetting implies that forgetting is the natural tendency. We forget the good things faster than we forget the hard ones. Keep a record of what God has done. Write it down. Look at it when memory fails. The record of his faithfulness is the foundation of future confidence." },
    { v:"He forgives all my sins and heals all my diseases.", r:"Psalm 103:3", d:"Hassolei'ach l'chol avoneki, who forgives all your iniquity. Haro'fe l'chol tachaluaiuki, who heals all your diseases. Both, forgiveness and healing, in the same verse, from the same God. He is not divided between spiritual concerns and physical ones. He who addresses the soul also attends to the body. When you bring the body's struggles to God, you bring them to the One who heals. Trust his timing and manner." },
    { v:"He fills my life with good things. My youth is renewed like the eagle's!", r:"Psalm 103:5", d:"Hamase'a tova nafsheki, who satisfies you with good. Titchadesh kannesher n'uraiuki, so that your youth is renewed like the eagle's. Not merely maintained. Renewed, titkhadesh, made fresh, brought back to a new state. This is what God does with those who trust him. The energy, the capacity, the resilience, these are God's renewing work in you. Receive them as what they are." },
    { v:"Give thanks to the Lord and proclaim his greatness. Let the whole world know what he has done.", r:"Psalm 105:1", d:"Hodu l'Adonai qir'u bishmo, give thanks to the Lord, call upon his name. Hodi'u va'amim alilotav, make known his deeds among the peoples. Make known: tell, declare, bring to the attention of others. Your health journey, the struggle, the grace, the showing-up-anyway, is a testimony. Someone near you is struggling in a way you have also struggled. Be willing to tell what God has done in you." },
    { v:"I will sing to the Lord because he is good to me.", r:"Psalm 13:6", d:"V'yasher b'Adonai ki gamal alai, I will sing to the Lord because he has dealt bountifully with me. Because, ki, the specific, personal experience of God's particular goodness in your particular life. Not because God is generally good. Because he has been good to you specifically, in this body, in this season. Find the evidence of his specific goodness to you. Sing from that." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and shield. I trust him with all my heart. He helps me, and my heart is filled with joy.", r:"Psalm 28:7", d:"Adonai uzi umaginni, the Lord is my strength and my shield. Uzi: my strength, my force, my power. Maginni: my shield, my protection. Offense and defense from the same source. The God who equips you for the effort is also the protection in your vulnerability. When you are weak, you are not exposed. The shield is still there. Trust him with the full range: the strong days and the weak ones." },
    { v:"I will bless the Lord who guides me; even at night my heart instructs me.", r:"Psalm 16:7", d:"Avarech et Adonai asher y'atzani, I will bless the Lord who gives me counsel. Af leilot yissruni kilyotai, even in the night my heart instructs me. The guidance does not stop when you sleep. The body repairs at night under God's attentive watch. The Spirit instructs in the quiet. Rest is not the absence of God's work in you. It may be when he is most actively working. Trust the night." },
    { v:"I know the Lord is always with me. I will not be shaken, for he is right beside me.", r:"Psalm 16:8", d:"Shiviti Adonai l'negdi tamid, I have set the Lord always before me. Ki mimini bal emot, because he is at my right hand I shall not be shaken. Tamid: always, continually, without ceasing. The practice of keeping God before you is a deliberate, sustained act. And it produces a particular result: bal emot, I shall not be shaken. Not because nothing threatens. Because of who is at the right hand." },
    { v:"No wonder my heart is glad, and I rejoice. My body rests in safety.", r:"Psalm 16:9", d:"Lachen samach libi vaygel k'vodi, therefore my heart is glad and my whole being rejoices. Af b'sari yishkon lavetach, even my body dwells secure. The whole person, heart, soul, and body, at genuine rest. My body dwells secure, lavetach, in safety, in confidence, without fear. Your body can rest with that quality of security when it is held by the One who never sleeps and never fails." },
    { v:"You will show me the way of life, granting me the joy of your presence and the pleasures of living with you forever.", r:"Psalm 16:11", d:"Toda'eni orach chaim, you make known to me the path of life. Sova semachot et panecha, in your presence there is fullness of joy. N'imot biminkha netzach, at your right hand are pleasures forevermore. The way of life, not mere existence but the full experience of what life is meant to be. The joy that comes from God's presence is not contingent on circumstances. It is fullness, sova, abundance, more than enough." },
    { v:"Surely your goodness and unfailing love will pursue me all the days of my life.", r:"Psalm 23:6", d:"Ach tov vachesed yirdefuni kol yemei chayai, surely goodness and mercy will pursue me all the days of my life. Yirdefuni: pursue me, chase after me, follow close behind me. Not wait for me when I return. Pursue me. Even on the days you are running from God, his goodness and mercy are following. You cannot outrun them. Let them catch you." },
    { v:"I remain confident of this: I will see the goodness of the Lord in the land of the living.", r:"Psalm 27:13", d:"Lule he'emanti lir'ot b'tuv Adonai b'eretz chayyim, unless I had believed that I would see the goodness of the Lord in the land of the living. The land of the living, here, now, in this body, in this life. Not only in the life to come. The Psalmist holds his confidence as something he has to work to maintain. I will see his goodness. He chooses to believe it in the present. So must you." },
    { v:"Oh, how great is your goodness, which you have stored up for those who fear you.", r:"Psalm 31:19", d:"Ma rav tuvcha asher tsafanta liyereicha, how great is your goodness which you have stored up for those who fear you. Tsafanta: stored up, hidden away, treasured in reserve. The goodness is not in short supply. It has been accumulated and held in reserve. The reverent trust of someone who fears God is what unlocks the stored goodness. Come to it in reverence. It is waiting." },
    { v:"The Lord is good, a strong refuge when trouble comes. He is close to those who trust in him.", r:"Nahum 1:7", d:"Tov Adonai l'maoze b'yom tzarah, the Lord is good, a stronghold in the day of trouble. V'yode'a chos'ei vo, and he knows those who take refuge in him. Yode'a: knows intimately, recognizes personally, has a particular acquaintance with. He is not indifferent to those who take refuge in him. He knows them by name. Your trust is not unnoticed. He is close to those who trust." },
    { v:"Praise the Lord, I tell myself, and never forget the good things he does for me.", r:"Psalm 103:2", d:"Barchi nafshi et Adonai v'al tishkichi kol g'mulav, bless the Lord, O my soul, and forget none of his benefits. Al tishkichi: do not forget. The command against forgetting implies that forgetting is the natural tendency. We forget the good things faster than we forget the hard ones. Keep a record of what God has done. Write it down. Look at it when memory fails. The record of his faithfulness is the foundation of future confidence." },
    { v:"May the God of hope fill you completely with joy and peace because you trust in him.", r:"Romans 15:13", d:"The God of hope, ho theos tes elpidos, the God who is the source of hope itself, fills you with all joy and peace as you trust. Not because your circumstances are hopeful. Not because things are going well. As you trust. The joy and peace are the result of the trusting, not the condition for it. You trust first. The joy and peace come as a consequence of the trusting, not as its prerequisite." },
    { v:"A peaceful heart leads to a healthy body.", r:"Proverbs 14:30", d:"Lev marpe chaim basar, a heart of healing is life to the body. Marpe: health, healing, tranquility of spirit. The Hebrew connects the state of the inner person directly to the health of the outer body. This is not metaphor. The cortisol of chronic anxiety, the physical cost of sustained contempt for yourself, these have measurable effects on the body. Tend the interior. It will show in the body over time." },
    { v:"Search for the Lord and for his strength; continually seek him.", r:"Psalm 105:4", d:"Dirshu Adonai v'uzzo, seek the Lord and his strength. Bakshu fanav tamid, seek his presence continually. Tamid: always, without stopping, as a perpetual habit. The seeking is not a season you enter and exit. It is the continuous posture of a life. Find ways to acknowledge him in the ordinary, before you begin, after you finish, in the middle when it gets hard." },
    { v:"Remember the wonders he has performed, his miracles, and the rulings he has given.", r:"Psalm 105:5", d:"Zichru nifle'otav asher asah, remember the wondrous works he has done. Zichru: remember, call to mind, actively recollect. Memory is a discipline. We remember the hard things naturally. The good things require intentional recollection. Build a record of what God has done in your body and your life. Look at it. It is the foundation for future confidence." },
    { v:"The Lord is good to those who depend on him, to those who search for him.", r:"Lamentations 3:25", d:"Tov Adonai l'qovav, the Lord is good to those who wait for him. Qavah: to wait, to hope, to be bound together with, like strands twisted into rope. The goodness of God is not uniformly distributed. It is specifically accessible to those who actually wait, who actually seek, who depend in the most literal sense. Not those who acknowledge that depending is a good idea. Those who do it. Depend. Seek. Receive what is available there." },
    { v:"Taste and see that the Lord is good. Oh, the joys of those who take refuge in him!", r:"Psalm 34:8", d:"Taste and see is an invitation to personal experience, not to secondhand belief. You can believe that food is nourishing without tasting it. But you cannot know it the same way. David is asking you to stop evaluating God from a distance and actually enter the experience of trusting him. The goodness he promises is not discovered through theology alone. It is found in the actual taking of refuge, the real act of stopping your own striving and leaning your weight on him." },
    { v:"Give thanks to the Lord, for he is good! His faithful love endures forever.", r:"Psalm 118:1", d:"Hodu l'Adonai ki tov, give thanks to the Lord for he is good. Ki l'olam chasdo, for his steadfast love endures forever. Not only when circumstances are good. Not only when the week goes well. His love is olam: eternal, without limit, not contingent on your performance. Build your gratitude on what does not change. That is the only kind that holds in every season." },
    { v:"Now may our Lord Jesus Christ himself and God our Father comfort you and strengthen you.", r:"2 Thessalonians 2:16–17", d:"Autos de ho kyrios hemon Iesous Christos kai theos ho pater hemon ho agapesas hemas kai dous paraklesen aionion, may our Lord Jesus Christ himself and God our Father who loved us and gave us eternal comfort. Paraklesis: comfort, encouragement, the presence of someone coming alongside you. The comfort arrives first. From it, strength grows. Rest in the comfort. The strength follows from the comfort, not the other way around." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and my shield. I trust him with all my heart.", r:"Psalm 28:7", d:"Adonai uzi umaginni, the Lord is my strength and my shield. Uzi: my strength, my force, my power. Maginni: my shield, my protection. Offense and defense from the same source. The God who equips you for the effort is also the protection in your vulnerability. When you are weak, you are not exposed. The shield is still there. Trust him with the full range: the strong days and the weak ones." },
  ],
  11: [
    { v:"Come to me, all of you who are weary and carry heavy burdens, and I will give you rest.", r:"Matthew 11:28", d:"Deute pros me pantes hoi kopiontes kai pephortiomenoi, come to me all who labor and are heavy laden. Kopiontes: those who are weary from hard work. Pephortimenoi: those loaded down with a heavy burden. Jesus does not say try harder, or get more efficient, or manage your rest better. He says come to me. The rest he offers is not a technique. It is a Person. The exhausted are not told to rest better. They are told to come to a specific place." },
    { v:"Take my yoke upon you. Let me teach you, because I am humble and gentle at heart, and you will find rest for your souls.", r:"Matthew 11:29", d:"Arate ton zugon mou eph' humas kai mathete ap emou, take my yoke upon you and learn from me. Hoti praus eimi kai tapeinos te kardia, for I am gentle and lowly in heart. The teacher you are learning from under this yoke is praus, meek, gentle, not harsh or demanding. He does not berate you for not being further along. He is gentle. The formation happening under his yoke is kind formation. Find rest in that." },
    { v:"For my yoke is easy to bear, and the burden I give you is light.", r:"Matthew 11:30", d:"Ho gar zugos mou chrestos kai to phortion mou elaphron estin, my yoke is easy and my burden is light. Chrestos: good, kind, easy to use, fitting perfectly. Elaphron: light in weight. Not because nothing is asked. Because the weight is properly distributed between two who share the yoke. A yoke fitted for one person is crushing. A yoke designed for two, where one of the two is God, is sustainable. Take it." },
    { v:"The Lord is my shepherd; I have all that I need. He lets me rest in green meadows.", r:"Psalm 23:1–2", d:"Adonai ro'i lo echsar, the Lord is my shepherd, I shall not want. Bin'ot deshe yarbitzeni, he makes me lie down in green pastures. Makes me lie down: yarbitzeni, to cause to lie down, to make rest happen. The rest is not earned. It is led into by the shepherd who knows what the sheep needs. The permission to rest does not come from the completion of the to-do list. It comes from the One who leads." },
    { v:"He leads me beside peaceful streams. He renews my strength.", r:"Psalm 23:2–3", d:"Al mei menuchot y'nahaleni, beside still waters he leads me. Nafshi y'shovev, he restores my soul. Y'nahaleni: to lead gently, to guide carefully, to conduct with care. The restoration comes in the leading beside still water, in the intentional stopping, the deliberate quiet, the willingness to be led to something you might walk past on your own. The body grows stronger during the rest. The soul is restored in the still." },
    { v:"He guides me along right paths, bringing honor to his name.", r:"Psalm 23:3", d:"Yancheni b'ma'aglei tzedek l'ma'an sh'mo, he leads me in paths of righteousness for his name's sake. Right paths, ma'aglei tzedek, not always easy ones. The path that brings honor to God may include the hard session, the uncomfortable discipline, the rest that feels like lost time. Right means correctly oriented, not comfortable. Trust the shepherd's sense of the path over your own preference for comfort." },
    { v:"Even when I walk through the darkest valley, I will not be afraid, for you are close beside me.", r:"Psalm 23:4", d:"Gam ki eileich b'gei tzalmavet lo ira ra ki attah imadi, even though I walk through the valley of the shadow of death, I will fear no evil, for you are with me. Imadi: with me, by my side, accompanying me. Not watching from a distance. Walking with you in the dark valley. The valley has a path through it, and someone who knows every valley is walking it beside you. You are not alone in the hard season." },
    { v:"Trust in the Lord with all your heart; do not depend on your own understanding.", r:"Proverbs 3:5", d:"Betach el Adonai b'chol libecha, trust in the Lord with all your heart. V'el binatcha al tishan, and do not lean on your own understanding. Tishan: to lean on, to rest your weight on, to use as support. The instruction is about where you put your weight. Full weight on God, not on your own analysis. Some of the paths that looked wrong from your limited view were exactly right. Trust the One with the complete picture." },
    { v:"Seek his will in all you do, and he will show you which path to take.", r:"Proverbs 3:6", d:"B'chol deracheicha da'ehu, in all your ways acknowledge him. V'hu yeyasher or'choteicha, and he will make straight your paths. In all your ways, every one, including the ones that seem too practical to involve God. Ask him about what your body needs. Ask him about the training decisions, the rest, the recovery. He makes paths straight for those who acknowledge him in all their ways." },
    { v:"Then you will have healing for your body and strength for your bones.", r:"Proverbs 3:8", d:"Rif'ut t'hi l'shorrecha v'shikui l'atzamoteicha, it will be healing to your body and refreshment to your bones. The practical effects of trusting God extend into the physical body. This is not metaphor. Chronic anxiety, the cortisol of sustained self-management, the physical cost of carrying what you were not designed to carry, these have measurable effects. Trust God with the carrying. Let the body rest from what it was never meant to hold." },
    { v:"Give all your worries and cares to God, for he cares about you.", r:"1 Peter 5:7", d:"The Greek is epiripsantes, to throw, to hurl, to cast. Peter does not say hand your worries gently to God. He uses the image of someone throwing something they cannot carry onto the back of someone strong enough to bear it. The care of God for you is the reason you can throw, not gently set down, not occasionally release, but throw, the weight onto him. He is not indifferent to what is crushing you. That is why the throwing is possible." },
    { v:"Be still, and know that I am God.", r:"Psalm 46:10", d:"Harpu ud'u ki anochi Elohim, be still and know that I am God. Harpu: let go, release, stop striving. Stillness is the posture that allows knowing. In the relentless motion of a life that does not slow down, stillness is an act of faith. The rest day is practice in this. Be still. Then know. The order cannot be reversed. The knowing comes in the stillness." },
    { v:"I lay down and slept, yet I woke up in safety, for the Lord was watching over me.", r:"Psalm 3:5", d:"Ani shachavti va'ishanah hekitzoti, I lay down and slept and I woke again. Ki Adonai yism'cheni, for the Lord sustains me. The sustaining happens at night. The muscle repair, the neurological consolidation, the restoration of the depleted, all of it happens while you sleep, under God's attentive watch. You do not have to manage your recovery. You have to enter into it. Lie down. The keeping is his work." },
    { v:"In peace I will lie down and sleep, for you alone, O Lord, will keep me safe.", r:"Psalm 4:8", d:"B'shalom yachdav eshkeva v'ishan, in peace I will both lie down and sleep. Ki attah Adonai livadad lavetach toshiveni, for you alone, O Lord, make me dwell in safety. Lavetach: in safety, securely, without fear. The sleep that comes from trusting God is qualitatively different from sleep that collapses from exhaustion. It is the rest of someone who knows the keeping is in better hands than theirs. Let it be that tonight." },
    { v:"He will not let you stumble; the one who watches over you will not slumber.", r:"Psalm 121:3", d:"Al yiten lamot raglecha al yanum shomrecha, he will not let your foot be moved; he who keeps you will not slumber. Will not slumber, al yanum, not for a moment, not in any circumstance. The watchfulness does not lapse. When the hard thing happens in the moment you were not ready, he was not asleep. He is already steadying you before you fully realize you are falling." },
    { v:"The Lord himself watches over you! The Lord stands beside you as your protective shade.", r:"Psalm 121:5", d:"Adonai shomrecha Adonai tzilcha al yad yeminecha, the Lord is your keeper; the Lord is your shade on your right hand. Shade, tzel, shadow, protection from the heat. In the relentless world of comparison, pressure, the constant demand to be more, God's presence is shade. Shelter from the heat of all the external voices. Stand in the shade. Not every moment must be productive. Some moments are meant for the shadow of the one who shelters you." },
    { v:"The Lord keeps you from all harm and watches over your life.", r:"Psalm 121:7", d:"Adonai yishm'recha mikol ra yishmar et nafshecha, the Lord will keep you from all evil; he will keep your life. From all evil, mikol ra. Not from all difficulty. Not from all struggle. From what would ultimately harm what matters most. You are kept, yishmar, guarded, protected. Even in the hard thing, the keeping is real." },
    { v:"The Lord keeps watch over you as you come and go, both now and forever.", r:"Psalm 121:8", d:"Adonai yishmar tzeitcha uvo'echa mei'atah v'ad olam, the Lord will keep your going out and your coming in from this time forth and forevermore. Mei'atah v'ad olam: from now and forever. The coverage does not have an expiration. It covers the mundane, the repetitive, the ordinary day of faithful living. Both now and forever. He sees every ordinary day you show up." },
    { v:"God gives rest to his loved ones.", r:"Psalm 127:2", d:"Achen yiten liditido shena, he gives sleep to his beloved. The word shena, sleep, comes as a gift, not as a reward for productivity. The one who stays up late toiling and rises early anxious has misunderstood the source of provision. God gives it. The striving that drives you past the point of rest is not faithfulness. It is the failure to trust that God can accomplish what you cannot accomplish by staying awake." },
    { v:"Don't worry about anything; instead, pray about everything.", r:"Philippians 4:6", d:"Me merimnate, do not be anxious. About anything, peri medenos. Instead, alla, in everything, en panti, by prayer and supplication with thanksgiving, proseuche kai deesis met eucharistias, let your requests be known to God. The anxiety has somewhere to go. It does not have to stay. Redirect it into prayer, every specific concern, named and offered. This is the practice of trust built one redirected worry at a time." },
    { v:"Tell God what you need, and thank him for all he has done.", r:"Philippians 4:6", d:"Me merimnate, do not be anxious. About anything, peri medenos. Instead, alla, in everything, en panti, by prayer and supplication with thanksgiving, proseuche kai deesis met eucharistias, let your requests be known to God. The anxiety has somewhere to go. It does not have to stay. Redirect it into prayer, every specific concern, named and offered. This is the practice of trust built one redirected worry at a time." },
    { v:"Then you will experience God's peace, which exceeds anything we can understand. His peace will guard your hearts and minds.", r:"Philippians 4:7", d:"Peace that exceeds understanding, it does not require favorable circumstances. This is the peace available in the middle of a hard training season, a slow week, a body that will not cooperate. Not produced by getting everything right. Given. Ask for the guard to be posted." },
    { v:"I am leaving you with a gift — peace of mind and heart. The peace I give is a gift the world cannot give.", r:"John 14:27", d:"Eirenen aphiemi humin, peace I leave with you. Eirenen ten emen didomi humin, my peace I give you. Not as the world gives, ou kathos ho kosmos didosin. The world gives peace when circumstances cooperate. Christ gives peace that operates inside the circumstances that do not cooperate. When the results are not there, when the season is long, when the hard thing will not resolve, this peace was given at the cross. It is still available." },
    { v:"Cast your cares on the Lord and he will sustain you; he will never let the righteous be shaken.", r:"Psalm 55:22", d:"Hashlech al Adonai y'havcha v'hu y'chalkelecha, cast your burden on the Lord and he will sustain you. Hashlech: to throw, to hurl, to cast away from yourself. Not gently place. Cast. The burden you are carrying, about your body, your progress, your season, is heavy enough to throw. God sustains, y'chalkelecha, to nourish, to maintain, to keep going, the one who casts. He sustains those who actually throw, not those who hold on while wishing they could." },
    { v:"When doubts filled my mind, your comfort gave me renewed hope and cheer.", r:"Psalm 94:19", d:"B'rov sar'apai b'kirbi, when the cares within me are many. Tanhumeicha y'shashu nafshi, your consolations cheer my soul. The cares are many, sar'apai, anxious thoughts, worrying doubts that crowd the inner life. And the consolation of God cheers, y'shashu, to delight, to exult, to be glad, the soul that is carrying them. Doubt and consolation can exist simultaneously. The consolation comes into the doubt. You do not have to resolve the doubt first." },
    { v:"The Lord is close to the brokenhearted; he rescues those whose spirits are crushed.", r:"Psalm 34:18", d:"Qarov Adonai l'nishb'rei lev, the Lord is near to the brokenhearted. V'et dak'ei ruach yoshi'a, and saves the crushed in spirit. Near, qarov, close, in immediate proximity. Not at a respectful distance. Near. When the spirit is crushed, dak'ei, broken into pieces, ground fine, this is where God is closest. Crushed spirits are locations of particular divine nearness. He is near to you in this." },
    { v:"He heals the brokenhearted and bandages their wounds.", r:"Psalm 147:3", d:"Haro'fe lishvurei lev umechabesh le'atzvotam, he heals the brokenhearted and binds up their wounds. Mechabesh: to wrap, to bandage, to bind with careful, skilled attention. The image is of a healer who knows exactly where the wound is and wraps it with competence and care. He is not treating a general condition. He is bandaging your specific wound. Bring it to him specifically." },
    { v:"Morning, noon, and night I cry out in my distress, and the Lord hears my voice.", r:"Psalm 55:17", d:"Erev vavoker v'tzaharayim asicha v'ehemeh, evening and morning and at noon I cry out and moan. V'yishma qoli, and he hears my voice. Three times a day. The distress is persistent, and so is the calling. God hears each time, not with diminishing patience, not with the sense that you have asked too many times. He hears every time. The prayer from genuine distress is a direct line, always open, always answered." },
    { v:"Come close to God, and God will come close to you.", r:"James 4:8", d:"Engisate to theo kai engisei humin, draw near to God and he will draw near to you. Engisate: move toward, come close, approach. The distance between you and God is not fixed. You move toward him. He moves toward you. The movement is mutual and it is always available. In the gym, on the rest day, in the middle of the hard week, draw close. He is coming toward those who come toward him." },
    { v:"In peace I will lie down and sleep, for you alone, O Lord, will keep me safe.", r:"Psalm 4:8", d:"B'shalom yachdav eshkeva v'ishan, in peace I will both lie down and sleep. Ki attah Adonai livadad lavetach toshiveni, for you alone, O Lord, make me dwell in safety. Lavetach: in safety, securely, without fear. The sleep that comes from trusting God is qualitatively different from sleep that collapses from exhaustion. It is the rest of someone who knows the keeping is in better hands than theirs. Let it be that tonight." },
  ],
  12: [
    { v:"Your word is a lamp to guide my feet and a light for my path.", r:"Psalm 119:105", d:"Ner l'ragli d'varecha, your word is a lamp to my feet. A ner: a small hand lamp that illuminates the step immediately in front of you, not the horizon. Not a floodlight. Not a map of the whole journey. Just the next step. You do not need to see where this is all going. You need enough light for today. Take the step in front of you. The light for the one after it will be there when you arrive." },
    { v:"The Lord is my light and my salvation — so why should I be afraid?", r:"Psalm 27:1", d:"Ori v'yishi, my light and my salvation. Ori, my light, the one who illuminates the path. Yishi, my salvation, the one who delivers me from what threatens. Both from the same person. The question David asks at the end, m'mi ira, of whom shall I be afraid, is not rhetorical. It expects an answer. The answer is: no one. When your light and your salvation are the same person, and that person is God, fear has no ground to stand on." },
    { v:"In the same way, let your good deeds shine out for all to see, so that everyone will praise your heavenly Father.", r:"Matthew 5:16", d:"Lampsato to phos hymon emprosthen ton anthropon, let your light shine before men. Hopos idosin hymon ta kala erga, so that they may see your good works. The light that shines is not dramatic. It is the consistent faithfulness that accumulates into something visible over time. The person who kept showing up, who kept caring for their body, who kept choosing the harder right thing, they become visible. Not because they advertised it. Because faithfulness is luminous." },
    { v:"You are the light of the world — like a city on a hilltop that cannot be hidden.", r:"Matthew 5:14", d:"Humeis este to phos tou kosmou, you are the light of the world. Ou dunatai polis krybeneai epano orous keimene, a city set on a hill cannot be hidden. Cannot be hidden, ou dunatai, it is impossible to hide it. The consistent, faithful life becomes visible without effort. People notice the energy that comes from a body honored. People notice the peace. Keep living faithfully. The visibility comes." },
    { v:"I am the light of the world. If you follow me, you won't have to walk in darkness.", r:"John 8:12", d:"Ego eimi to phos tou kosmou, I am the light of the world. Ho akolouthon emoi ou me peripatese en te skotia, whoever follows me will not walk in darkness. Walk, peripateo, to live, to conduct the daily life. Following Christ illuminates not just the spiritual questions but the practical ones: how to train, how to rest, how to think about this body you inhabit. Follow him into the ordinary decisions. You will not walk in darkness." },
    { v:"For everything there is a season, a time for every activity under heaven.", r:"Ecclesiastes 3:1", d:"L'chol z'man v'et l'chol chefetz tachat hashamayim, for everything there is a season, and a time for every matter under heaven. Season, z'man, an appointed time, a set period. Your training has been seasonal. Times of great progress and times of holding. Times of intensity and times of necessary rest. This is not failure. This is design. Which season are you in? What does this one require of you?" },
    { v:"Yet God has made everything beautiful for its own time.", r:"Ecclesiastes 3:11", d:"Et hakol asah yafeh b'ito, he has made everything beautiful in its time. Yafeh: beautiful, fitting, appropriate. God makes beauty from the specific moments he places you in, not despite them. The hard season has a beauty the easy one cannot produce. The slow season has something the fast one cannot teach. The rebuilding after setback produces something the uninterrupted progress cannot. Ask what beauty is being made in this one." },
    { v:"I know that there is nothing better for people than to be happy and to do good while they live.", r:"Ecclesiastes 3:12", d:"Yada'ti ki ein tov bam ki im lismoch v'la'asot tov b'chayav, I know that there is nothing better for them than to rejoice and to do good while they live. Do good while you live, b'chayav, in his life, during the span of his days. The health you are building is the resource for the doing of good. You are not building it for appearance. You are building it for the capacity to do what you are called to do with whatever time you have." },
    { v:"Here now is my final conclusion: Fear God and obey his commands, for this is everyone's duty.", r:"Ecclesiastes 12:13", d:"Sof davar hakol nishma et ha'Elohim yera v'et mitzvotav sh'mor, the end of the matter, all has been heard: fear God and keep his commandments, for this is the whole of man. The whole of man, kol ha'adam, the entire person, the complete human being. Not a part of life. The whole of it. This is the conclusion of the wisest man who ever lived, after exhaustive examination of every alternative. Build toward a life that can be summarized this way." },
    { v:"Search me, O God, and know my heart; test me and know my anxious thoughts.", r:"Psalm 139:23", d:"Chaqar, to search, to investigate thoroughly, to probe to the depths. David is asking for complete exposure. No hidden corner, no performance for God's benefit, no curated version of himself presented for divine inspection. He wants God to see everything and to show him what God finds. This is not masochism. It is the prayer of someone who trusts the Searcher more than he trusts his own self-assessment. Ask for it. Trust what he finds." },
    { v:"Point out anything in me that offends you, and lead me along the path of everlasting life.", r:"Psalm 139:24", d:"Derek olam, the way of everlasting, the ancient path, the road that has always led somewhere permanent. David asks to be led on it. Not the comfortable path. Not the easy path. The path that leads to what is actually lasting. Ask God to lead you on it in how you train, in how you rest, in how you speak to yourself about your body. The path is real. The leading is available. Stay on it one faithful day at a time." },
    { v:"How precious are your thoughts about me, O God. They cannot be numbered!", r:"Psalm 139:17", d:"The Hebrew word for precious is yaqar, rare, costly, of great weight. The thoughts God has toward you are not passing observations. They are weighted with value, too numerous to count. He is not merely aware of you. He is actively thinking toward you, right now, in this ordinary moment. You were thought about today before you did anything to deserve attention. That is a different kind of being known than anything a person can offer." },
    { v:"I can never escape from your Spirit! I can never get away from your presence!", r:"Psalm 139:7", d:"Ana eileich meiruchecha v'ana mipaneicha evrach, where shall I go from your Spirit? Or where shall I flee from your presence? Evrach: to flee, to run away, to escape. The answer implied is: nowhere. There is no place you can go where God is not. The sessions where you felt alone, he was there. The seasons where faith was thin, he was there. You cannot get away from his presence even when you feel farthest from it." },
    { v:"You go before me and follow me. You place your hand of blessing on my head.", r:"Psalm 139:5", d:"Achor vazedem tzartani, you hem me in, behind and before. Vatashit alai kapecha, and lay your hand upon me. Behind, the past, the year closing. Before, the future, the year opening. And the present: your hand upon me right now. You are going into the future preceded by God and followed by God, with his hand on you in this moment. There is no safer position than this." },
    { v:"Such knowledge is too wonderful for me, too great for me to understand!", r:"Psalm 139:6", d:"Pil'iah da'at mimeni nisgavah lo uchal lah, such knowledge is too wonderful for me; it is high; I cannot attain it. The extent of God's attention to you, the completeness of his knowledge of you, the constancy of his presence with you, David does not try to comprehend it. He calls it wonderful and lets it be beyond comprehension. You cannot think your way to the bottom of it. Receive it. Worship the God who exceeds your ability to understand him." },
    { v:"For his unfailing love toward those who fear him is as great as the height of the heavens above the earth.", r:"Psalm 103:11", d:"Ki kigvoah shamayim al ha'aretz, as high as the heavens are above the earth. Gavar chasdo al y'rei'av, so great is his steadfast love toward those who fear him. As high as the heavens above the earth, the maximum distance the ancient mind could conceive. His love is not calibrated to your performance. It is scaled to the dimensions of the universe. Do not shrink the love of God to fit your understanding of your own worth." },
    { v:"He has removed our sins as far from us as the east is from the west.", r:"Psalm 103:12", d:"Kirckok mizrach mima'arav, as far as the east is from the west. Hirchiq mimenu et p'sha'einu, so far does he remove our transgressions from us. East from west, not north from south, which have poles and could be measured. East from west: a direction that has no end, a distance without a meeting point. The failures of the year that is closing, God has removed them. Not filed them. Removed them. Begin from cleared ground." },
    { v:"The Lord is like a father to his children, tender and compassionate to those who fear him.", r:"Psalm 103:13", d:"K'racheim av al banim richam Adonai al y'rei'av, as a father shows compassion to his children, so the Lord shows compassion to those who fear him. Rachem: compassion, the deep tenderness of a parent for a child. The Father who watched this year is not keeping a tally of failures. He is moved by what moves you. He is tender toward what is tender in you. He is compassionate. You are tended by this kind of God." },
    { v:"For he knows how weak we are; he remembers we are only dust.", r:"Psalm 103:14", d:"Ki hu yada yitzreinu zachur ki afar anachnu, for he knows our frame; he remembers that we are dust. He knows, yada, intimately, from the inside. He formed you, yatzar, shaped you as a potter shapes clay. He remembers what you are made of. His expectations of you are calibrated to your humanity. He is not surprised by your limitations. He made them. He loves you inside them. Let that settle whatever performance anxiety you carry." },
    { v:"But the love of the Lord remains forever with those who fear him.", r:"Psalm 103:17", d:"V'chesed Adonai mei'olam v'ad olam al y'rei'av, but the steadfast love of the Lord is from everlasting to everlasting on those who fear him. From everlasting to everlasting, mei'olam v'ad olam. Both directions, without end. Including the seasons you are not proud of, the weeks that were harder than expected, the days you did not show up the way you intended. The love does not change. This is the constant." },
    { v:"Praise the Lord, I tell myself, and never forget the good things he does for me.", r:"Psalm 103:2", d:"Barchi nafshi et Adonai v'al tishkichi kol g'mulav, bless the Lord, O my soul, and forget none of his benefits. Al tishkichi: do not forget. The command against forgetting implies that forgetting is the natural tendency. We forget the good things faster than we forget the hard ones. Keep a record of what God has done. Write it down. Look at it when memory fails. The record of his faithfulness is the foundation of future confidence." },
    { v:"May the God of hope fill you completely with joy and peace because you trust in him. Then you will overflow with confident hope.", r:"Romans 15:13", d:"The God of hope, ho theos tes elpidos, the God who is the source of hope itself, fills you with all joy and peace as you trust. Not because your circumstances are hopeful. Not because things are going well. As you trust. The joy and peace are the result of the trusting, not the condition for it. You trust first. The joy and peace come as a consequence of the trusting, not as its prerequisite." },
    { v:"Now may our Lord Jesus Christ himself and God our Father comfort you and strengthen you in every good thing you do and say.", r:"2 Thessalonians 2:16–17", d:"Autos de ho kyrios hemon Iesous Christos kai theos ho pater hemon ho agapesas hemas kai dous paraklesen aionion, may our Lord Jesus Christ himself and God our Father who loved us and gave us eternal comfort. Paraklesis: comfort, encouragement, the presence of someone coming alongside you. The comfort arrives first. From it, strength grows. Rest in the comfort. The strength follows from the comfort, not the other way around." },
    { v:"For a child is born to us, a son is given to us. And he will be called: Wonderful Counselor, Mighty God, Everlasting Father, Prince of Peace.", r:"Isaiah 9:6", d:"Ki yeled yulad lanu ben nitan lanu, for a child is born to us, a son is given to us. Nitan: given, donated, offered as gift. This child is not something we produced. He is something given. Wonderful Counselor, Pele Yoetz, one whose counsel is too wonderful to be merely human. Mighty God, El Gibor, the full power of God in human form. Everlasting Father, Avi Ad, the eternal, parental care that never ends. Prince of Peace, Sar Shalom, the one whose presence produces complete wholeness. All four are true of the same person. Receive them." },
    { v:"Glory to God in highest heaven, and peace on earth to those with whom God is pleased.", r:"Luke 2:14", d:"Doxa en hupsistois theo, glory in the highest to God. Kai epi ges eirene en anthropois eudokias, and on earth peace among people of his good pleasure. Eirene: shalom, not the absence of conflict but the presence of everything in its right place. This is what the incarnation brings, not an escape from the world but the arrival of wholeness into it. The glory goes upward. The peace comes down. Receive what has come down." },
    { v:"For this is how God loved the world: He gave his one and only Son, so that everyone who believes in him will not perish but have eternal life.", r:"John 3:16", d:"Houtos gar egapesen ho theos ton kosmon, God so loved the world. Edoken, he gave, he donated, he offered at cost. His one and only Son. Not a concept of giving. An actual, costly, irreversible act. For you, not the idealized version, not the version that has it together, you as you actually are. This is the foundation on which everything else stands. It is not shaken by your performance." },
    { v:"The night is almost gone; the day of salvation will soon be here. So remove your dark deeds like dirty clothes, and put on the shining armor of right living.", r:"Romans 13:12", d:"He nux prokopsen he de hemera engiken, the night is far gone; the day is at hand. Apobalometha oun ta erga tou skotous, let us cast off the works of darkness. Endusometha de ta hopla tou photos, let us put on the armor of light. Put on, endusometha, to clothe yourself, to put on as a garment. What you wear determines how you move. Put on the armor of light deliberately, as a morning choice. The night of old patterns is passing." },
    { v:"I remain confident of this: I will see the goodness of the Lord in the land of the living.", r:"Psalm 27:13", d:"Lule he'emanti lir'ot b'tuv Adonai b'eretz chayyim, unless I had believed that I would see the goodness of the Lord in the land of the living. The land of the living, here, now, in this body, in this life. Not only in the life to come. The Psalmist holds his confidence as something he has to work to maintain. I will see his goodness. He chooses to believe it in the present. So must you." },
    { v:"This means that anyone who belongs to Christ has become a new person. The old life is gone; a new life has begun!", r:"2 Corinthians 5:17", d:"The word Paul uses is ktisis, a new creation, like the first act of Genesis. He is not talking about someone who cleaned up their life. He is talking about someone who died. The old self built on performance, on the approval of others, on the shame of not being enough, that person is gone. Most people live as if they are merely reformed. Paul says you are replaced. The practical question is not whether this happened. It did. The question is which version of yourself you are going to act from today." },
    { v:"Surely your goodness and unfailing love will pursue me all the days of my life, and I will live in the house of the Lord forever.", r:"Psalm 23:6", d:"Ach tov vachesed yirdefuni kol yemei chayai, surely goodness and mercy will pursue me all the days of my life. Yirdefuni: pursue me, chase after me, follow close behind me. Not wait for me when I return. Pursue me. Even on the days you are running from God, his goodness and mercy are following. You cannot outrun them. Let them catch you." },
    { v:"And I am certain that God, who began a good work within you, will continue his work until it is finally finished.", r:"Philippians 1:6", d:"The Greek word is epiteleo, to bring to completion, to carry through to the end. Paul uses it of God the way a craftsman uses it of his own work. God does not start things and lose interest. He does not begin a good work in you and walk away when progress is slow or the material is difficult. The confidence Paul describes is not in your consistency. It is in God's commitment to finish what he started. Your job is to show up. His job is to complete the work." },
  ],
};

function getTodayScripture() {
  const now = new Date();
  const month = now.getMonth() + 1;
  const day = now.getDate();
  const mm = String(month).padStart(2,"0");
  const dd = String(day).padStart(2,"0");

  // Special dates first
  if (SPECIAL[`${mm}-${dd}`]) return { ...SPECIAL[`${mm}-${dd}`], isSpecial: true };

  // Liturgical season overrides
  const season = getLiturgicalSeason(now);
  if (SEASONS[season]) return { ...SEASONS[season], isSpecial: true };

  // Pick from monthly array by day
  const arr = BY_MONTH[month] || BY_MONTH[1];
  const entry = arr[(day - 1) % arr.length];
  return { v: entry.v, r: entry.r, d: entry.d || null, season: null, isSunday: now.getDay() === 0 };
}

// ── Sunday reflection prompts ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
const SUNDAY_PROMPTS = [
  "What is one thing your body did this week that you are grateful for?",
  "Where did you feel God's strength most clearly in your training this week?",
  "What would it look like to honor God with your body more fully this coming week?",
  "What is one area of your health you want to bring to God in prayer today?",
  "Where did you hold back this week — in training, in rest, or in trusting God?",
  "What did this week's effort reveal about your character? What do you want to build on?",
  "How can the strength you are building serve the people around you this week?",
  "What do you need to release — a comparison, a shame, a fear — before the new week begins?",
];

function getSundayPrompt() {
  const week = Math.floor(new Date().getDate() / 7);
  return SUNDAY_PROMPTS[week % SUNDAY_PROMPTS.length];
}

// ── Cross SVG ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
function CrossMark({ color = "#555" }) {
  return (
    <svg width="13" height="15" viewBox="0 0 13 15" fill="none" style={{ flexShrink: 0, marginTop: "2px" }}>
      <rect x="5.5" y="0" width="2" height="15" rx="1" fill={color} />
      <rect x="0" y="5" width="13" height="2" rx="1" fill={color} />
    </svg>
  );
}

// ── Component ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
export default function DailyScripture({ accent = "#2563a8", inHeader = false }) {
  const today = new Date().toISOString().slice(0, 10);
  const notesKey = `scripture_notes_${today}`;
  const [expanded, setExpanded] = useState(false);
  const [notes, setNotes] = useState(() => {
    try { return localStorage.getItem(notesKey) || ""; } catch { return ""; }
  });

  const scripture = getTodayScripture();
  const isSunday = new Date().getDay() === 0;
  const sundayPrompt = isSunday ? getSundayPrompt() : null;

  function handleNotes(e) {
    setNotes(e.target.value);
    try { localStorage.setItem(notesKey, e.target.value); } catch {}
  }

  if (!scripture) return null;

  const seasonLabel = scripture.season || (isSunday ? "Sunday · Rest & Reflection" : "Today's Word");

  return (
    <div style={{
      ...(inHeader
        ? { margin: "0 0 12px 0", borderRadius: "6px", overflow: "hidden", border: "1px solid #2a2a2a", background: "#1a1a1a" }
        : { margin: "10px 14px", borderRadius: "10px", overflow: "hidden", border: "1px solid #222", background: "#111" }
      ),
      ...F,
    }}>

      {/* Always-visible header — tap to expand */}
      <button onClick={() => setExpanded(p => !p)} style={{
        width: "100%", background: "none", border: "none", cursor: "pointer",
        padding: inHeader ? "10px 12px" : "13px 15px",
        display: "flex", alignItems: "flex-start", gap: "10px", textAlign: "left", ...F,
      }}>
        <CrossMark color={accent} />
        <div style={{ flex: 1, minWidth: 0 }}>
          <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.22em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: accent, marginBottom: "5px" }}>
            {seasonLabel}
          </div>
          {/* Full verse always shown */}
          <div style={{ fontSize: "13px", color: "#e8e0cc", lineHeight: "1.7", fontStyle: "italic" }}>
            "{scripture.v}"
          </div>
          {/* Reference always shown */}
          <div style={{ fontSize: "10px", color: accent, marginTop: "6px", letterSpacing: "0.06em" }}>
            — {scripture.r}
          </div>
        </div>
        <span style={{ color: "#444", fontSize: "10px", flexShrink: 0, paddingTop: "2px" }}>
          {expanded ? "▲" : "▼"}
        </span>
      </button>

      {/* Expanded section — reflection + notes */}
      {expanded && (
        <div style={{ borderTop: "1px solid #1e1e1e" }}>

          {/* Reflection */}
          {scripture.d && (
            <div style={{ padding: "14px 15px 12px" }}>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.18em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#555", marginBottom: "9px" }}>
                Reflection
              </div>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "13px", color: "#b8b0a0", lineHeight: "1.85" }}>
                {scripture.d}
              </div>
            </div>
          )}

          {/* Sunday prompt */}
          {isSunday && sundayPrompt && (
            <div style={{ padding: "10px 15px 12px", borderTop: "1px solid #1e1e1e" }}>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.18em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#555", marginBottom: "9px" }}>
                This week
              </div>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "13px", color: "#b8b0a0", lineHeight: "1.8", fontStyle: "italic" }}>
                {sundayPrompt}
              </div>
            </div>
          )}

          {/* Personal notes */}
          <div style={{ padding: "10px 15px 14px", borderTop: "1px solid #1e1e1e" }}>
            <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.18em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#444", marginBottom: "7px" }}>
              Your notes
            </div>
            <textarea
              value={notes}
              onChange={handleNotes}
              placeholder="Add your own reflection..."
              style={{
                width: "100%", boxSizing: "border-box",
                background: "#1a1a1a", border: "1px solid #2a2a2a",
                borderRadius: "5px", color: "#c8c0b0", fontSize: "12px",
                lineHeight: "1.65", padding: "8px 10px", resize: "none",
                outline: "none", minHeight: "70px", ...F,
              }}
              rows={3}
            />
          </div>

        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
